<HEADLINE> Report on Weapons Hand-Over in N.Ireland Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON June 29 (Xinhua) - The international body set up to
oversee the handing over of paramilitary weapons in Northern
Ireland has agreed to delay its report - raising hopes that a
breakthrough may still be possible.
</P>
<P>
The release of General John de Chastelain's views on the
readiness of terrorist groups to disarm had been expected to be a
key factor in the on-going talks.
</P>
<P>
General de Chastelain, whose report will now be released on
Wednesday, a day behind schedule, reached his decision after a
lunchtime meeting with Prime Minister Tony Blair and Irish premier
Bertie Ahern.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the talks on Tuesday afternoon suggested Sinn Fein
could be ready to make some movement on decommissioning. The
party's president, Gerry Adams, said: "We do not contemplate
failure."
</P>
<P>
"I think we can get there. It's a matter of bringing the right
political will," he added.
</P>
<P>
The UK and Irish prime ministers have both stressed that a deal
can be reached in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Both Blair and Ahern had separate talks with the Sinn Fein
leader and Martin McGuinness as the last-ditch efforts continued
to broker a deal before Blair's Wednesday deadline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
