<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Welcomes Mediation Efforts on Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Minister for Kashmir
Affairs Abdel Meguid Malek on Tuesday expressed welcome to
international mediation efforts aimed at helping solve the
Pakistani-Indian conflict on Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters while stopping over at Cairo
International Airport en route to Morocco from Jordan, Malek said
Egypt can play a key role in this respect as Cairo maintains good
ties with New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Pakistani Minister of Religious Affairs Raja Zafer
Ul Haq extended a request from Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to help mediate in the ongoing
conflict over Kashmir between the two South Asian neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Ul Haq said Mubarak "has promised to work on" the issue.
</P>
<P>
India accused Pakistan of backing Muslim guerrillas who
infiltrated into the Indian-controlled part of Kashmir and has
been shelling the hilltops on which it said the infiltrators are
entrenched.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan denied it has militarily backed the infiltrators,
saying it has only given moral support to those "freedom fighters."
</P>
<P>
Troops of the two countries have been exchanging fire along the
border in Kashmir over the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan called for negotiations with India, but New Dheli
rejected international intervention and said no talks were
possible before the intruders were expelled from its territory.
</P>
<P>
Malek is on an Arab tour to rally support for his country's
stand on the Kashmir issue. He has visited Qatar, Kuwait, Lebanon
and Jordan, and will travel to Morocco and Tunisia after leaving
Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
