<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Gets 5 Years in Prison for Selling Atom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A 64-year-old German who sold
atomic secrets to Iraq was sentenced to five years in prison
Tuesday by a court in the southern city of Munich.
</P>
<P>
The court said, businessman Karl-Heinz Schaab was found guilty
of treason and foreign trade law violation for helping Iraq to
design an atomic device, Media here reported.
</P>
<P>
It said, Schaab supplied the country in 1989 and 1990 with the
technical expertise for a high-powered centrifuge which could have
enabled Iraq to produce weapons-grade uranium.
</P>
<P>
Schaab gave himself up to authorities at Frankfurt airport on
his return to Germany from Brazil last September. He had been
detained in Rio de Janeiro and then released after Brazil decided
not to extradite him to Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
