<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Common Currency not on Agenda, Chretien Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Using the U.S. dollar as a "common
currency is not on the agenda" of this week's cabinet retreat,
Canadian Prime Minister said Tuesday as he entered the two-day
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"There is no such discussion in the government at all," he told
reporters amid local media speculations about the possibility of a
currency union with the United States.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister instead put priority of the meeting on a
free-trade zone for all the Americas, rather than the North
America Free Trade Agreement group of the United States, Canada
and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
"Right now it's a three-way deal, we want to expand to a larger
deal with the rest of the Americas," he said.
</P>
<P>
Local media believe, however, trade issues between Canada and
the United States carry weight on the table during the gathering
of ministers.
</P>
<P>
One of the hot topics is reported to be the modernizing of the
customs system between the two countries to make things more
efficient and less stringent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
