<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disagreement Remains in DRC Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Disagreement remained over three
main points in a draft document for ending the 11-month conflict
in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), participants attending
Lusaka peace talks said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
DRC Foreign Minister Abdoulaye Yerodia Ndombasi said, "our main
 reservation is the question of a new national army. We don't
understand what is meant by the integrated army."
</P>
<P>
The ongoing ministerial meeting, attended by defense and
foreign ministers from 14 Southern African Development Community,
as well as Rwanda, Uganda and Libya, discussed a document drafted
by a technical committee which calls on rebel groups to be
integrated into a national Congolese army with their arms intact.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the meeting said the rebels demand to negotiate a
new political structure in the country, which is rejected by the
government, and the rebels insist all foreign forces be withdrawn
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Some officials close to the meeting said that they were
optimistic that a deal could be struck, however they said that a
quick breakthrough is not realistic.
</P>
<P>
"We have made considerable progress, but success lies in
addressing these three issues," said Bizima Karaha, security chief
and spokesman for the main rebel group.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Zambian government which was hosting the talks
said they were hopeful a cease-fire agreement would be reached.
</P>
<P>
The conflict in the vast former Zaire, the third largest
African country, has drawn armies from at least six African
countries and threatens to engulf the continent.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican Ambassador to Zambia Christofa Jamo told journalists
that the meeting which started Monday would reconvene Tuesday
evening to let delegations involved in the conflict to iron out
their differences.
</P>
<P>
But he could not tell when the talks would end. If the
ministers approved the draft document, the heads of state would
meet in Lusaka to endorse the signature of the agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
