<HEADLINE> U.S. Expects Egypt to Broaden Relations with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Tuesday that it expects the Egyptian government to "broaden and
deepen" its relations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk, briefing
reporters on the ongoing visit by Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, said Egypt could contribute to the Middle East peace
process by warming up to Israel again as a new Israeli
government under Labor leader Ehud Marak has given new hope of
progress toward that direction.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has already made positive remarks about Prime
Minister-elect Barak, who is on the verge of forming a coalition
to support peace moves with the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said on Monday that he expected Barak to visit Egypt
soon and was optimistic about revising peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"I think he's a good man, a very cautious man, promising ...
He's contacted me several times and I have great hopes that he's
going to make progress in the peace process ...," he said in a
interview on CNN.
</P>
<P>
Indyk described Egypt as "our strategic partner in the Middle
East" with a common interest and a common vision.
</P>
<P>
"The President (Bill Clinton) wants to consult with President
Mubarak on how we can together help to push the peace process
forward on all fronts with the objective of achieving a
comprehensive peace," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
