<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Egyptian Ministries Secured Against Y2K Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- About 97 percent of Egypt's
government ministries and agencies have been secured against the
Y2K bug, an official announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The remaining computers will be fully Y2K compliant by
September, said Ahab Elwy, head of the Central Agency for Public
Mobilization and Statistics.
</P>
<P>
"The outlook is optimistic," said Elwy, who also heads a
technical committee formed to handle the problem.
</P>
<P>
The committee is part of Egypt's 1998 government program to
ward off the chaos that is expected to occur around the world
because of the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
Most older computers, computerized equipment and software
programs were programmed to recognize only the last two digits of
a year. These computers may misread the year 2000 as 1900, causing
technical malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
This confusion can affect the computer systems for electricity,
water, bank, prison locks, payrolls, elevators and gas pumps.
</P>
<P>
Elwy said all of the government's 166 mainframes and 108,518
computers have been adjusted to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
His committee receives weekly reports from the ministries and
agencies with a stress on the "contingency plans" designed as
back-up in case technical failures occur on or after January 1,
2000, Elwy said.
</P>
<P>
The private sector also reports to the technical committee and
major companies have been vigorously working to solve the problem,
Elwy said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Claims to Have Put Out of Action 1,976 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia claimed that it has
put out of action 1, 976 Eritrean soldiers during fightings in the
past two days near the Mereb River, according to a press release
issued by the Ethiopian government Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian side claimed that Eritrea started the attack near
the Mereb River and that "the Ethiopian defense forces
successfully repelled the offensives" launched from Sunday to
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The fighting continued Tuesday with low intensity, said the
release.
</P>
<P>
However, there is no response from the Eritrean side available
here.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, the Ethiopian airforce bombed Eritrea's Assab
airport, a strategic military target, severely damaging the
airport runway.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea had blamed each other for initiating more
fighting in the wake of renewed calls from the Organization of
Africa Unity (OAU) and the U.N. Security Council for immediate and
unconditional cease-fire between the two Horn of Africa countries.
</P>
<P>
The war between the two Horn of Africa neighbors broke out in
early May of 1998 over a disputed stretch of border.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have agreed to a peace framework put forward by
the OAU, but neither seems to have turned their words into action.
</P>
</TEXT>
