<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Park Installs Radio Units to Enhance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's Bwindi National Forest
Park has received 20 radio units donated by Motorola to help
enhance the security of visitors.
</P>
<P>
Moses Ali, Second Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of
Tourism, Trade and Industry who received the donations Tuesday,
pledged that the government would make best use of the equipment.
</P>
<P>
The radio units would mainly be used by park staff to
communicate among themselves and to call for help in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
The national park is famous for its rare mountain gorillas. It
boasts of more than 300 gorillas, more than half of the world's
total.
</P>
<P>
The park hit headlines in early March when eight foreign
tourists were murdered in the park.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan troops were sent to guard the park soon afterwards.
</P>
<P>
The park reportedly accounts for nearly 70 percent of revenue
of Uganda' s Wildlife Authority and foreign visitors usually have
to book their tickets one year in advance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
