<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official Denies Israeli Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Ezz-Eddin El-Sherief, governor of
Tulkarm in the West Bank, denied on Tuesday a report by the "Voice
of Israel" radio that Palestinian police had opened fire at
Israeli policemen.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli radio said Palestinian police opened fire at
Israeli policemen on June 23 at the Khodori checkpoint in Tulkarm.
</P>
<P>
El-Sherief said in a press release that, on the day, two
Israeli police vehicles carrying 12 plain-clothed policemen
intruded the Palestinian-controlled "Zone A" in Tulkarm, assaulted
and tried to abduct a plain-clothed Palestinian police officer.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian policemen in the area opened fire in the air to
scare off the Israeli policemen and managed to rescue the
Palestinian officer, he added.
</P>
<P>
The governor condemned the Israeli radio of fabricating reports
and attempting to create chaos and instability.
</P>
<P>
The issue was referred to the Palestinian-Israeli Liaison
Committee, he added, noting that a fact-finding committee was set
up to probe the issue as well as the Israeli intrusions of the
areas controlled by the Palestinian National Authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
