<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Religious Party to Support Barak's Government From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Israel's religious party United
Torah Judaism (UTJ) has decided not to join Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak's emerging coalition government but to support it from
outside.
</P>
<P>
Announcing its decision here on Tuesday, the party said,
however, it might join the coalition government at a later time.
</P>
<P>
UTJ said that during its talks with a negotiation team of
Barak's One Israel alliance on Monday and Tuesday, the two sides
reached a compromise to set up a committee fully empowered to make
decisions on the issue of drafting religious students into the
army.
</P>
<P>
The issue has been the ultra-orthodox UTJ's major concern.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the religious students over the age of 24 can
be drafted for military training, that special uniforms will be
designed for them and that the defense minister has the sole power
to decide who will be recruited into the army.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here said the UTJ's decision is not a final
one, and that the UTJ is waiting for Shas to announce its decision
whether to join the coalition, which is expected to be made in a
meeting of the Council of Torah Sages of Shas on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The main problem standing in the way of Shas' entry into the
coalition is its insistence on full control of the Religious
Affairs Ministry, whereas Barak has promised the National
Religious Party (NRP) that it might share the ministry with Shas
in a rotation agreement.
</P>
<P>
Barak has asked the two religious parties to solve the problem
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Meantime, the left-wing Meretz, which has signed a coalition
agreement with One Israel, said it will make a final decision on
whether to joint the coalition government within several days in
the face of possible inclusion of Shas into the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Meretz has objected to Shas' participation in the coalition,
accusing Shas, which has controlled the Interior Ministry for
about 15 years, of misusing public money for its own interests.
</P>
<P>
The next few days will be crucial for Barak in his coalition
forming effort as he has to submit the cabinet list to the
acting Knesset (parliament) one week before July 9, the deadline
for his government formulation stipulated by the election law.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who won the May 17 prime ministerial election, has to
rally support from other smaller parties to form a broad-based
coalition government because his One Israel alliance got only 26
seats in the 120-seat Knesset. 
</P>
</TEXT>
