<HEADLINE> Turkish Peacekeeping Troops to Leave for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkish peacekeeping troops will
start to leave Turkey on Thursday to join the multi-nation forces
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of the Turkish troops is expected to leave
Ankara on July 1 and will arrive at Kosovo by road, Turkey's
state-run TV reported here Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The second batch will embark on the way to Kosovo on Friday by
train while the third and the final batches will fly to the
Mecedonian capital to Skopje on July 7 and then travel on to
Prisren.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, a farewell ceremony was held for the Turkish
troops at the military facilities in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish troops are scheduled to be deployed in the
sector of Kosovo allocated to the U.S. surveillance.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish peacekeeping troops are composed of 987 personnel
including 55 officers, 115 non-commissioned officers, 30 expert
privates, 14 civil servants and other privates.
</P>
<P>
As a NATO member, Turkey dispatched 11 Turkish F-16 fighter
jets to participate in NATO's air strikes against Yugoslavia
since March 24.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Turkey's Anatolia News Agency reported
the number of Kosovar refugees leaving their camps in Turkey
has exceeded 5,000 by Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Some 18,000 Kosovars took shelters in Turkey during the Kosovo
crisis. 
</P>
