<HEADLINE> World Economy in Gradual Recovery: U.N. Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The world economy is in a
gradual recovery process but economic growth in 1999 remains low,
the U.N. Economic and Social Council quoted a latest U.N. survey
as saying on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After 2 years of financial turbulence and a marked slowdown in
global economic growth, the world economy is gradually recovering
with economic prospects improved and global financial markets
showing signs of stabilization, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
Financial contagion from the Brazilian currency crisis at the
beginning of 1999 was contained and there has been some
restoration of capital flows to a number of emerging markets,
added the report.
</P>
<P>
The survey will be among the documents before the delegates of
the 1999 substantive session of the U.N. Economic and Social
Council in Geneva from next Monday to July 30.
</P>
<P>
Despite these short-term improvements, economic growth in 1999
remains inadequate and markedly lower than at mid-decade,
particularly for the majority of developing and transition
economies, the survey goes on.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for the rest of 1999 and beyond suggests only a
minor overall improvement and in a number of cases, the economic
situation will continue to deteriorate, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
In the majority of countries, growth for the foreseeable future
will fall far short of what is necessary to effect a substantial
improvement in living standards and a reduction in the number of
people living in poverty. it added.
</P>
<P>
The growth of world output at less tan 2% in 1998 was about
half of that in 1997. Growth in all groups of countries slowed
down but the setback to the developing countries was greater.
</P>
<P>
Their average growth of only 1.7% in 1998 was below that of the
developed countries for the first time since the 1980s and
contrasted markedly with the average growth of 5% or more that
they had achieved earlier in the decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
