<HEADLINE> Iran Offers to Help Lebanon's Infrastructure Rebuilding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Tuesday offered to help
Lebanon rebuild its roads and bridges which were destroyed in
Israel's bloodiest air strikes on Lebanon since 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Iran is ready to provide any assistance to help rebuild
Lebanese infrastructure from the davastation of the Israeli air
attack," said Mohammed Irani, charge d'affairs ad interim of the
Iranian embassy in Beirut, in a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Irani made the announcement after meeting with Lebanese Minister
of Transportation and Public Works Najib Mikati along with a
delegation of Iranian ministry of transportation and roads.
</P>
<P>
Irani said the delegation has made a trip to the striken
bridges linking Beirut and its south and is working on a plan to
help have it repaired.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, Israel launched the biggest air raids on
Lebanon since its 1996 "Grapes of Wrapth" operations, which killed
eight people and wounded 64.
</P>
<P>
The country's two power stations, three bridges and a
telephone relay station were also destroyed in the attacks which
followed a cross-border Katyusha barrage by guerrillas of
Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed that its air attacks served as a retaliation for
Hezbollah's offensive which killed two Israelis, whereas the
Iranian-backed group argued it fired rockets into northern Israel
to avenge the wounding of six Lebanese civilians of Israeli
shelling.
</P>
<P>
Syria has offered an emergency electricity supply while
Billionaire Saudi Prince Walid bin Talal, whose mother is a
Lebanese, has agreed to foot the bill of rebuilding the
destroyed power stations estimated at 30 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
