<HEADLINE> Greece to Sign Relevant Agreements With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Greece on Tuesday voiced its
willingness to sign relevant agreements with neighboring Turkey
concerning the issues raised in a letter sent by the Greek Foreign
Minister George Papandreou to his Turkish counterpart Ismail Cem
last week.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Yiannis Nikolaou said that the New York talks between the two
ministers on Wednesday would take place within the framework of
issues raised in Papandreou's letter.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Greece would have no reason not to sign the
relevant agreements if Turkey had no objection to agreements being
reached on these issues.
</P>
<P>
In his letter replying to an earlier one from Cem, Papandreou
reportedly accepted the proposal for talks on terrorism, on a
multilateral or bilateral basis, but he also proposed talks aimed
at reaching agreement on a series of other issues such as
environment, economic cooperation and cultural issues.
</P>
<P>
Nikolaou stressed once again that apart from the issues set out
in Papandreou's letter, Greece was not willing to discuss any
other issue, and in particular it would refuse to discuss matters
stemming from unilateral Turkish demands and Turkish
aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Greece and Turkey have been strained over
decades for their disputes in the territorial waters, air space
limits and the delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean
Sea, and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, no progress has been made in their bilateral
relations although the two rivals have tried hard to improve such
ties. 
</P>
