<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence Rises Again in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer confidence moved up
for the eighth consecutive month in June, signaling even stronger
economic growth in the coming months, the Conference Board said in
a report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Consumer Confidence Index stands at 138.4
in June up from 137.7 in May, the highest level in more than 30
year. The all-time high for the Consumer Confidence Index was
142.3 in October 1968.
</P>
<P>
"Great expectations are continuing to fuel consumer
confidence," said Lynn Franco, Associate Director of The
Conference Board's Consumer Research Center. "While recent gains
in confidence are modest, consumers now account for almost 70
percent of U.S. economic growth, and current confidence levels
point to even stronger economic growth next year than previously
projected."
</P>
<P>
In another report Monday, The Conference Board said driven by
robust consumer spending, the U.S. economy will grow even more
strongly this year and into 2000 than previously projected.
</P>
<P>
The Board now projects the economic growth to run in the 4
percent to 4.5 percent range this year and more than 3 percent in
2000. This is an increase from the 3.5 percent growth rate that
the Board projected for the past six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
