<HEADLINE> Jordan, Palestinians Agree to Push Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and the Palestinians agreed
Tuesday to build up mechanisms of bilateral cooperation and to
push forward the deadlocked Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced in a joint statement issued after
talks between Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Raouf Rawabdeh and
visiting Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Jordan expressed its readiness to stand
by the Palestinians to break the deadlock in the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, the two leaders discussed the prospects for
the final status negotiations, especially with regard to issues of
water, security, borders and refugees, Jordan`s official news
agency Petra said.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh described his talks with Arafat as fruitful, and said
both sides shared identical views on various issues as well as the
working plans for the next stage, Petra said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat thanked Jordan for its consistent support for the
Palestinians, and he said his talks with King Abdullah Bin Hussein
and Prime Minister Rawabdeh as "fruitful and constructive."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader left Amman for home after his two-day
working visit to the desert kingdom.
</P>
<P>
During the talks with Arafat on Monday, King Abdullah called
Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak to resume peace talks with
the Palestinians, which remained deadlocked since 1996, and to
pave the way for the final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated Jordan`s support for all legitimate rights
of the Palestinians, including the establishment of an independent
Palestinian state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
