<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Records Surplus in Balance of Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- South Africa recorded a
surplus of 6.2 billion rand or one billion U.S. dollars in the
balance of payments on current account for the first quarter of
this year, the South African Reserve Bank said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure, seasonally adjusted and annualized, was a
significant turnaround on the past four quarters which were all in
the red, according to the central bank of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The balance on current account in the third and fourth quarters
of 1998 showed deficits of 19.8 billion rand (3.3 billion dollars)
and 18.5 billion rand (3.08 billion dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
The balance of payment figures in the first quarter of 1999
were boosted by stronger merchandise exports, particularly of
mineral products which were assisted by a weaker rand, and a
considerable reduction in imports, mainly of manufactured goods
and farming products.
</P>
<P>
Gold exports were however well down and the outlook is far from
rosy for future export revenue from the yellow metal following
announcements of the proposed gold sales by the Bank of England
and the International Monetary Fund which has pushed bullion
prices down to 20-year lows.
</P>
<P>
The quarterly bulletin of the South African central bank
reported merchandise exports for the first quarter of 1999 at
149.1 billion rand (24. 85 billion dollars) compared to just 132.1
billion rand (22 billion dollars) for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Merchandise exports in the first three months were also 5.5
billion rand (917 million dollars) ahead of the third quarter of
1998, when the best level was recorded last year.
</P>
<P>
"The compression of aggregate demand in the economy contributed
to the reversal of the deficit on the current account into a
surplus," said the bank.
</P>
<P>
"Expressed in terms of a seasonally adjusted and annualized
rate, the current account turned from a deficit of 19.8 billion
rand in the third quarter of 1998, or 2.7 percent of gross
domestic products (GDP), to a surplus of 6.2 billion rand in the
first quarter of 1999, equivalent to 0.8 percent of GDP."
</P>
<P>
It said the value of merchandise imports (seasonally adjusted
and annualized) which had declined from 165.9 billion rand (27.65
billion dollars) in the third quarter of last year to 158.5
billion rand (26.4 billion dollars) in the fourth quarter, had
contracted further by 10.2 percent to 142.4 billion rand (23.73
billion dollars) in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The physical quantity of imported goods, the bank said, had
increased by 6.2 percent in the third quarter of last year and by
0.8 percent in the fourth. But it had declined by almost 13
percent in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the physical quantity of total merchandise exports
increased by about 8.1 percent in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
