<HEADLINE> U.N. Council to Focus on Poverty Eradication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Despite unprecedented
economic and social progress in the last half century, the global
challenge of poverty remains, according to U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Annan's remarks are contained in his report to the Economic and
Social Council which meets next month on poverty eradication and
other matters in its annual session in Geneva, the council said in
New York Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There are close to 1 billion adults unable to read or write
most of whom are women, Anna's report goes on.
</P>
<P>
Three quarters of a billion people have no access to health
services and malnutrition affects over 800 million people.
</P>
<P>
Many millions lack access to safe water, and many millions more
have a life expectancy of less than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
The greatest number of people below the poverty line live in
Asia, but the depth of poverty is greater in sub-Saharan Africa
than any other region. Among the poor, women and children are
suffering the most.
</P>
<P>
The number of fully working children between the ages of five
and 14 is at least 120 million or about 250 million if those for
whom work is a secondary activity are included.
</P>
<P>
Annan calls for immediate and full debt relief to the least
developed low-income countries and longer-term capital flows to
support their development objectives.
</P>
<P>
The council's substantive session from July 5-30 will tackle
questions like the role of employment in poverty eradication, the
gender dimension, capacity-building, the development of Africa and
disaster-relief assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
