<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand bids to Reduce Workforce in Public Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet approved here
Tuesday an early retirement program proposed by the Office of
Civil Service Commission in a bid to improve efficiency by
reducing manpower in the public sector, a Government House press
release said.
</P>
<P>
The early retirement package, to be applied on voluntary basis,
is expected to be taken up initially by 30,000 civil servants at a
saving to the state of almost 15 billion baht (416.7 million U.S.
dollars) over two years.
</P>
<P>
This package is part of the government's plan to cut 120,000
jobs in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
The target group of the package is those who are aged 50 or
over and those who have been serving in the public sector for 25
years or more.
</P>
<P>
Special compensation will be given to the early retired
officials including a gratuity equal to seven months' wages and an
additional sum to be paid monthly along with the pension.
</P>
<P>
Government officials can begin applying for the program since
October 1, 1999 when the next fiscal year starts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
