<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Begins Organized Return of Kosovar Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) began the organized repatriation
of hundreds of thousands of Kosovar refugees by taking over 300
from camps in Macedonia to their homes in Kosovo's provincial
capital of Pristina on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 325 returnees from Stenkovec refugee camps 1 and 2 north of
the Macedonian capital of Skopje made their return trip aboard 10
buses organized by the UNHCR and the International Organization
for Migration, said a UNHCR press release available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Returning refugees is always the most satisfying part of our
work," said Dennis McNamara, UNHCR's Special Envoy for the former
Yugoslavia and Albania. "But it is also a major challenge when you
have a large refugee population like this one that is so anxious
to return."
</P>
<P>
Of some 800,000 refugees in regional asylum countries at the
beginning of June, the UNHCR said, more than half have already
gone back on their own, making one of the fastest spontaneous
returns seen by the refugee agency in decades.
</P>
<P>
The early returns occurred despite warnings from the UNHCR, U.N.
peacekeeping force (KFOR) in Kosovo and others that refugees might
face an uncertain security situation, heavy damage in many areas
and the lack of an international support system back in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR said that dozens have been wounded or killed by mines
and many have returned to find their towns and villages destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The refugee agency estimated that there are about 67,000
refugees still in Macedonia, 32,400 in camps and 34,700 living
with host families.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR is also expected to begin organized returns of refugees
from Albania, where about 209,000 refugees remain. Some 46,000
refugees are now in the Republic of Montenegro and another 21,000
in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
