<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia Calls For S-S Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Namibia Foreign
Minister Theo Ben Gurirab Tuesday called for improved Afro-Asian
solidarity and more efforts from bodies like the Non-Aligned
Movement (NAM) and the G-77 for better South-South cooperation in
the era of globalization.
</P>
<P>
"Time has come for Asia and Africa to share our common roots
for a stronger and democratic South," Gurirab told a function
organized here Tuesday by the Association of Indian Africanist.
</P>
<P>
"Improved South-South cooperation in economy, politics, culture
and technical fields is a must," added Gurirab, who arrived here
on Sunday for a five-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
"We need the NAM and G-77, along with China, more than ever to
make a combined effort to regionally and internationally
strengthen South-South cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
With their big markets, trade opportunities, strong export
capacities and achievements in science and technology, Gurirab
said, India and other Asian countries must do more and more
business with Africa to improve South-South Solidarity.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Gurirab met Indian caretaker Prime Minister
Atal Behari Vajpayee and External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh,
during which he expressed his understanding of India's stand on
the current conflict with Pakistan in Kashmir, an official of the
External Affairs Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Gurirab also called on Indian President Kocheril Raman
Narayanan Tuesday, and during their 30-minute meeting, they
discussed NAM's role in prevailing international scenario and
steps to strengthen it specially in the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Namibia is currently a non-permanent member of the U.N.
Security Council and Gurirab has been endorsed by the African
group of countries as the candidate for the next president of the
U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations must become a democratic institution
unfettered by any hegemonistic tendencies of the cold war days, he
said.
</P>
<P>
India was among the first to recognize the ruling South West
African People's Organization (SWAPO) as the sole representative
of the Namibian people and allowed it to open an office in New
Delhi with full diplomatic privileges and status.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee paid an official visit to Namibia last August, during
which a protocol was signed on foreign office consultations
between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
