<HEADLINE> Namibia Foreign Minister Visits India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Namibia expressed its
understanding Tuesday of India's stand on the current conflict
with Pakistan in Kashmir, according to an official of the External
Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian view was conveyed here Tuesday by visiting Foreign
Minister Theo Ben Gurirab during his meeting with Indian caretaker
Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee and External Affairs Minister
Jaswant Singh, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Singh briefed Gurirab on the developments in the Kargil sector
of Kashmir and in South Asia, and the two ministers also discussed
other international developments including the Kosovo crisis and
economic issues.
</P>
<P>
Gurirab, who arrived here on Sunday on a five-day official
visit, called on Indian President Kocheril Raman Narayanan
Tuesday, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
During the 30-minute meeting, Narayanan and Gurirab discussed
the role of the Non-Aligned Movement in prevailing international
scenario and steps to strengthen it specially in the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
Namibia is currently a non-permanent member of the U.N.
Security Council and Gurirab has been endorsed by the African
group of countries as the candidate for the next president of the
U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
India was among the first to recognize the ruling South West
African People's Organization (SWAPO) as the sole representative
of the Namibian people and allowed it to open an office in New
Delhi with full diplomatic privileges and status.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee paid an official visit to Namibia last August, during
which a protocol was signed on foreign office consultations
between the two countries. 
</P>
