<HEADLINE> UAE Reiterates Support for Ethnic Albanians in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) Tuesday reiterated its support for ethnic Albanians in the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo, where peacekeeping efforts are going
on as refugees are returning home.
</P>
<P>
The UAE will continue its support for Kosovars, until
"comprehensive and just peace" is achieved there, said Deputy
Prime Minister Sheikh Sultan Bin Zayed Al Nahyan in a meeting
with his Albanian counterpart Aller Mitta, currently on a visit
to the UAE.
</P>
<P>
Aller Mitta said through his visit he sought to express the
gratitude of the Albanian government and people to the UAE for
its support during the refugee crisis.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians, most of them
Muslims, fled Kosovo to Albania and other neighboring countries
during 79 days of air strikes against Yugoslavia by U.S.-led
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) forces.
</P>
<P>
The air strikes were launched on March 24 on the excuse
that the Yugoslav government abuse human rights by cracking down
on ethnic Albanian separatists.
</P>
<P>
The UAE backed NATO's air strikes and sent huge amounts of
relief materials to the refugees, in addition to building an
airport in Kukes, Albania, for transporting relief supplies.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has also sent troops to join NATO in the peacekeeping
in Kosovo following the end of the air strikes earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The NATO-led peacekeeping is being carried out under a
U.N. resolution following a Russia-mediated agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
