<HEADLINE> Thailand Urges Investors to Join Venture Capital Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will give
incentives to private investors for establishing or joining
venture capital funds to support small and medium-sized
enterprises (SMEs) in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Panpree patranukorn, advisor to Thai Industrial Minister, was
quoted by Thai News Agency as saying Tuesday that the incentives
could include tax exemptions on fund management and bonus for
private investors setting up the funds.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministry planned to promote diverse venture capital
funds, aimed at increasing business opportunities and liquidity of
local SMEs.
</P>
<P>
The privately established venture capital funds, participated
by both Thai and foreign investors, would be similar to the Thai
Venture Capital Fund to be set up by the Thai government with the
initial capital of 1-3 billion baht (27.8-83.3 million U.S.
dollars), the advisor said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has planned to set up the Thai Venture
capital Fund to support its industrial restructuring program in 13
sectors and to serve as a pilot for other similar initiatives.
</P>
<P>
The privately-initiated venture capital funds would not only
benefit Thai SMEs, but also help boost and expand investment
projects in the country, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
