<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Budget Disbursement Below Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The budget spending during the
first eight months of the fiscal year 1999 is well below target,
the Thai cabinet meeting announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A Government House press release on the weekly cabinet meeting
said withdrawn budget by the end of May was at 426.1 billion baht
(11.8 billion U.S. dollars), or 51.6 percent of the total budget,
which is lower than the targeted 441.5 billion baht (12.3 billion
dollars), or 53.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the Finance Ministry, one of the main obstacles
for the lower-than-targeted disbursement of budget for the 34
government agencies is the liquidity crunch faced by government
projects contractors.
</P>
<P>
Delayed construction projects by early rains and delayed land
expropriation also lowered the pace of investment spending using
the budget.
</P>
<P>
To accelerate government spending, the Finance Ministry has
asked government agencies to place budget disbursement requests
with the ministry before September 20.
</P>
<P>
The Budget Bureau has been asked to make a quarterly report to
the Cabinet on the progress of disbursement.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry has also vowed to reduce the red tape by
limiting the budget approval procedure within one day.
</P>
<P>
By running a public sector deficit of up to six percent in the
1999 fiscal year, the government wanted to achieve a one percent
growth in gross domestic product (GDP). But delayed disbursement
has caused concern that this target will not be met. 
</P>
</TEXT>
