<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Senate Clears Five More Ministerial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Senate Tuesday cleared
five of the seven ministerial nominees submitted on Monday by
President Olusegun Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
Among those cleared were retired Lt. Gen. Theophilus Danjuma
and Yomi Edu, two of the seven whose names were returned last week
by the 109-member upper house.
</P>
<P>
The Senate passed 42 of President Obasanjo's 49 ministerial
nominees on June 23 and the seven were returned to the president.
</P>
<P>
The clearance of former Chief of Army Staff Lt. Gen. Danjuma
without debate came during the resumed sitting of the Senate to
consider the new nominees presented by President Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
Danjuma, speculated to head the defense ministry of Nigeria's
first civilian government for 15 years, returned to the West
African country at the weekend after treatment of "depression"
abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Senate said that the clearance of the retired general, who
just bowed to the members after the announcement of his clearance,
was in recognition of "his meritorious service to the country."
</P>
<P>
Among the newly cleared nominees were the three substitute
nominees of the minority All People's Party (APP) whose candidates
were among the seven rejected earlier by the Senate, and two other
substitute names presented by the ruling People's Democratic Party
(PDP).
</P>
<P>
The clearance of a total 47 ministerial nominees paved the way
for a new civilian government of the Fourth Republic, which is
expected to be sworn in on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
