<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Deplores Attack on UN Mission Office in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Tuesday called on the Indonesian police to investigate an
incident in which a regional office of the U.N. Mission in East
Timor (UNAMET) was attacked.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General deplores in the strongest terms today's
attack on the Maliana regional office of UNAMET," statement issued
by Annan's spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
According to UNAMET, some 100 persons, reportedly
pro-integration militia members, threw rocks and stones at the
office while UNAMET staff and local people took refuge there.
</P>
<P>
Several people were seriously injured, one UNAMET staff member
was hurt and the office was extensively damaged, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Annan holds the Indonesian Government accountable "for allowing
such an attack to occur, and deems any assault on UNAMET personnel
or property completely unacceptable", it added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief's representatives in the field "have protested
the attack to the Indonesian authorities in Jakarta and Dili",
East Timor capital, the statement went on.
</P>
<P>
UNAMET has been established recently to organize and conduct a
vote to determine the future of East Timor, considered by the
United Nations as a non-self-governing territory since 1976 when
Indonesia annexed it.
</P>
<P>
The territory had been a Portuguese colony until 1975 when an
internal rift led to Indonesia's occupation.
</P>
<P>
Under U.N. mediation, Indonesia and Portugal reached an
agreement on May 5 to hold a so-called popular consultation in the
territory to see if the majority of its 800,000 inhabitants wants
special autonomy within Indonesia or independence.
</P>
<P>
The voting day had been scheduled for August 8, but the U.N.
put it off till two weeks away because of safety and logistics
considerations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
