<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elephant Hunting to Be Allowed in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- After an interval of nine years,
Mozambique will allow the hunting of elephants as a sporting
event, Carlos Agostinho do Rosario, the Minister of Agriculture
and Fisheries, revealed here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Ministers approved recently a decree allowing
the restoration of elephant hunting in the southern African
country as a sporting event at its 17th meeting, the Mozambique
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique joined the Convention on International Trade of
Endangered Species (CITES) in 1990 and stopped elephant hunting
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the decree won't be effective until
the minute rules are made out which will take about a month.
</P>
<P>
Elephant hunting is aimed to control the number of elephants in
the country and reduce illegal hunting.
</P>
<P>
The elephants hunted will not be traded but instead be turned
into decorations, otherwise it is against the CITES.
</P>
<P>
Only areas with enough number of elephants could be qualified
for hunting, while under legitimate inspection, the minister
noted, adding that no hunting is allowed in national parks and
natural reserves.
</P>
<P>
There are currently about 17,200 elephants in Mozambique.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
