<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopians Allowed to Run Private Radio, TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's parliament, the
House of People's Representatives, Tuesday approved the
broadcasting proclamation, allowing the establishment of private
radio and television (TV) stations in the Horn of Africa country.
</P>
<P>
The proclamation stipulates that only Ethiopians are allowed to
 establish radio and TV stations.
</P>
<P>
It also stipulates that religious and political organizations
cannot set up radio and TV stations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the parliament also approved, at its 35th regular
session, the 13.9-billion-birr (8.121 birr equal to one U.S.
dollar) budget earmarked for 1999/2000 financial year, 25 percent
more than the 11.1-billion-birr budget of current 1998/1999
financial year ending on July 7, 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, among the new budget,
6.2 billion birr is recurrent, 2.5 billion birr is capital and the
remaining some 3.1 billion birr will be apportioned among the
regional states in the form of subsidy.
</P>
<P>
The 2.5 billion birr of capital expenditure is 14 percent less
than that of 2.9 billion birr capital expenditure in 1998/1999
financial year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
