<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Launches First Yen Global Bond Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) on Tuesday launched its first Japanese yen global bond
issue of 100 billion yen (approximately 826 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The ten-year bonds carry a semiannual coupon of 1.9 percent and
an issue price of 99.449 percent. This was the first benchmark
bond in the global yen market for almost a year and a half.
</P>
<P>
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Tokyo-Mitsubishi International
are the lead managers of the issue, which matures on July 8, 2009.
</P>
<P>
The issue attracted a broad-based favorable response from
investors worldwide, the Washington-based bank said. About 60
percent of the bonds were sold in Japan and other parts of Asia,
30 percent in Europe and the Middle East, and around 10 percent in
North America.
</P>
<P>
The proceeds of the issue will be used to help finance the
social and economic development of the IDB's Latin American and
Caribbean member countries, the IDB said.
</P>
<P>
With this financing, the IDB has raised a total of 5.8 billion
dollars during this fiscal year through 19 separate transactions.
Among these it has executed its first global bond issues in three
currencies: Japanese yen, Canadian dollars and New Zealand
dollars. The bank has raised 3.4 billion dollars through three
U.S. dollar global bonds.
</P>
<P>
The IDB's funding program for the year calls for up to 9
billion dollars to be borrowed in a combination of currencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
