<HEADLINE> Mubarak Says Sees New Dawn with New Israeli Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak said on Tuesday that he saw a "new dawn" for the Middle
East peace with the imminent change of government in Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The road ahead is long and the obstacles many, but we have
seen the birth of a new dawn," said Mubarak, speaking at a
honorary degree ceremony at George Washington University.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is visiting Washington this week for consultations on
the next steps in peace talks after Israeli Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak takes office.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak began meeting with U.S. leaders on Monday. He is due to
have talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk said Clinton
wanted to consult with Mubarak on "how we can together help to
push the peace process forward on all fronts with the objective
of achieving a comprehensive peace."
</P>
<P>
Indyk said the United States expected Egypt to broaden and
deepen its relationship with Israel under a new government under
the leadership of Barak.
</P>
<P>
"This is the intention of the government of Egypt, and it will
be very helpful, as both the Israeli and Arab sides in
negotiations confront very difficult decisions," Indyk said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has made very positive remarks about Barak, calling
him "a good man, a very cautious man, promising" in a interview
with CNN on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He told CNN that he expected Barak to visit Egypt soon and
was optimistic about reviving peace talks in the Middle East.
