<HEADLINE> New Group to Work With World Bank on Combating Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A special high-level
anti-corruption advisory group is working with the World Bank to
attack and prevent corruption in East Asia, the bank announced on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The group, which is still gaining members, brings together
former government officials, academics, business people and
officials from civil society, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The advisory group was formed to review the bank's regional
anti-corruption strategy and to assist the bank in assessing and
addressing corruption issues in its client countries in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
At the first meeting held in Washington in mid-June, the group
set its course on a dual track: first, advising the World Bank's
regional management on specific initiatives to address this
problem, and second, sharing information on what is happening in
various countries, including assessing the effectiveness of the
bank's regional anti-corruption strategy and its actions.
</P>
<P>
"This group, with its experience and breadth of views, is
extremely important for us to move forward in our anti-corruption
work," said Jean-Michel, Vice President for the World Bank's East
Asia and Pacific Region. 
</P>
