<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL-EU Summit Concludes in Rio de Janeiro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Latin American,
Caribbean and European Union heads of state or of government
demanded Tuesday the establishment of a just free trade system and
the strengthening of the financial systems to prevent future
economic crises.
</P>
<P>
Both stances are contained in the Declaration of Rio and in the
Joint Declaration signed by the leaders attending the first summit
of Latin America (LA), the Caribbean and the EU that started
Monday and concluded Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The leaders agreed that the next summit will be held in Spain
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-six leaders and representatives of 47 countries attended
the first LA-EU summit held in Rio de Janeiro, the capital of the
Brazilian state of the same name.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's President Fernando Henrique Cardoso and his Chilean
counterpart Eduardo Frei proposed the adoption of mechanisms of
protection against the speculative financial flows.
</P>
<P>
The world needs "new institutions that will regulate adequately
the enormous financial flows that characterize the global
economy," said Frei, demanding the EU not to exclude Latin America
from this process.
</P>
<P>
Cuban President Fidel Castro hailed the implementation of the
unique European currency, the euro, and condemned the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) policy.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said in the joint declaration that the
strengthening of the financial systems of the countries of the two
continents will contribute to establishing a world economic and
financial system more dynamic and stable that will guarantee the
prevention of future crises.
</P>
<P>
The leaders agreed to take an active part in the design of a
new international financial architecture, in view of the
seriousness and recurrence of financial crises and the severity of
their impact at a national and international level.
</P>
<P>
Those attending the summit said that the stability will permit
both regions to benefit from the integration of the markets of
capitals and reduce the risks implied by their volatility.
</P>
<P>
The leaders proposed to hold during the next World Trade
Organization (WTO) ministerial meeting a new round of trade
negotiations of integral nature without excluding any sector,
directed to reduce tariff and non tariff barriers to the commerce
of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and of government decided to unite their
efforts to guarantee the full and timely implementation and
effective application of the commitments assumed during the
Uruguay Round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
