<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cooperation Urged with U.N. Mission in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
on Tuesday called on all parties to cooperate fully with the
United Nations Mission in East Timor (UNAMET) for a smooth voting
to determine the future of the territory.
</P>
<P>
The council, after meeting on the subject and considering a
recent report by Secretary-General Kofi Annan, arrived at a
presidential statement which urges Annan to take "all necessary
steps to ensure full deployment" of UNAMET by July 10.
</P>
<P>
East Timor had been a Portuguese colony until 1975 when an
internal rift led to Indonesia's occupation. In the following
year, Indonesia annexed it, making it a province.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, considering East Timor a non-self-governing
territory, reached an agreement with Indonesia and Portugal on May
5 to hold a so-called popular consultation in East Timor to see if
the majority of its 800,000 inhabitants wants autonomy or
independence.
</P>
<P>
The voting date had been set for August 8, but Annan postponed
it to two weeks away for security and logistics considerations.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council "warmly welcomes" the channels of
communication set up between UNAMET and the Indonesian
authorities, the opening of talks between representatives of all
sides in East Timor and progress towards making the Commission on
Peace and Stability operative, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
But it is seriously concerned about the lack of conditions to
begin the operational phases of the consultation process and the
acts of violence by the militias and other armed groups.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council urges the Indonesian Government and the
pro-integration and pro-independence groups to continue to enhance
cooperation with UNAMET, to allow the popular consultation to go
ahead in a timely manner," the statement said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
