<HEADLINE> Official: Drugs Threaten Russian National Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The spread of drugs inside Russia
has reached a point that the country's national security is
threatened, a high-ranking official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Putin, director of the Federal Security Service, the
main successor to the KGB, told a meeting in the Kremlin that
state-level measures should be taken to fight this social vice.
</P>
<P>
He said the surge in the number of minors and young people
abusing drugs also put the nation's future in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
Putin, who also serves as chairman of the top Russian advisory
body, the Security Council, attributed the drug spread to
declining standards of living, degeneration of some members of the
society, and the lax fight on drugs.
</P>
<P>
The conference, dedicated to narcotics control, came up with
some basic principles for the fight against drugs and called for
coordinated actions by various departments and agencies.
</P>
<P>
The number of drug users in Russia rose 3.6 times since 1994.
In 1998 alone, the authorities registered 190,000 cases of drug
smuggling. Up to 116,000 people were convicted and 110,000
received disciplinary sanction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
