<HEADLINE> European Shares in Mixed Mode As US Rate Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- London shares fell heavily in
volatile trading Tuesday as the world waited for U.S. interest
rate decision.
</P>
<P>
On the day dominated by speculation about the scope of a U.S.
rate hike. The FTSE 100 sank to a sharply lower close of 6307.1,
down 98.6 points and near a session low of 6301.1.
</P>
<P>
The fall came despite a strong performance on Wall Street in
the afternoon and a record close the previous night by Tokyo's
Nikkei Index.
</P>
<P>
Rate-sensitive banking stocks, often the most vulnerable at
times of Fed-related uncertainty, saw some substantial erosion on
the session.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Scotland fell 3.6 percent, off its earlier lows, while
Lloyds eased 0.1 percent and HSBC suffered a nearly 3 percent loss
in a setback tied to its Asian performance.
</P>
<P>
Bucking the trend, shares of British insurer Prudential jumped
4.1 percent, to 935 pence, making it one of the top gainers on the
FTSE 100, after a report in the Financial Times highlighted
Prudential's efforts at corporate overhaul.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Dax share index closed flat as investors sat on their
hands ahead of the Fed's meeting which could raise the cost of
borrowing. The Dax ended the day's trading up 2.58 points at
5359.53 points.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC 40 index of leading components resisted the
soft start on Wall Street to close 0.9 percent higher at 4503.83,
a gain of 38.60 points.  
</P>
</TEXT>
