<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Volumes of "Mao Zedong Works" Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The 6th, 7th and 8th volumes of "
Mao Zedong Works" have been published by the People's Publishing
House, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
All eight volumes of "Mao Zedong Works", another comprehensive
and multi-volume works of the late Chairman Mao after the "
Selected Works of Mao Zedong", have now been published.
</P>
<P>
The publication was approved by the Communist Party of China (
CPC) Central Committee and compiled by the Party Literature
Research Center of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
The publication includes 803 literary works, incorporating 2.3
million Chinese characters, which could not be found in the "
Selected Works of Mao Zedong". The works were selected from
writings, lectures and recorded speeches of Mao Zedong in the 1921-
1976 period.
</P>
<P>
The first and second volumes of "Mao Zedong Works" were
published in December 1993, and the 3rd, 4th and 5th volumes were
published in September 1996. These five volumes compose most of
Mao's works written in the democratic revolution period before the
founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
The 6th, 7th and 8th volumes of "Mao Zedong Works" incorporate
some 300 literary pieces, which were written after 1949; many of
them were published for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The 6th volume includes 137 works, incorporating some 330,000
Chinese characters, which were written in the period from October
1949 to December 1955.
</P>
<P>
The 7th volume comprises of 72 works, of some 290,000 Chinese
characters, composed in the 1956-1958 period.
</P>
<P>
And the 8th volume includes 90 works, of a further 290,000
Chinese characters, written by Mao Zedong in the 1959-1975 period.
</P>
<P>
The Cultural Revolution (1966-1975), launched by Chairman Mao,
was a mistake of overall importance. Therefore, "Mao Zedong Works"
only includes some key treatises written by Mao on reforming
overseas publicity, differentiating the three worlds, making
breakthroughs in diplomacy, and adjusting policies affecting
literature and art.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
