<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Says No Intention to Cross LoC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Caretaker Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee said on Wednesday that India now had no intention
to cross the line of control (LOC) to clear the Kargil area in
Kashmir of "Pakistani intruders."
</P>
<P>
"As of now, we have no intention of crossing the LoC," Vajpayee
told a press conference in Lucknow, about 490 km east of New
Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Asked why India was hesitating to cross the LoC to choke the
supply lines of the so-called "infiltrators" as suggested by
Indian defense experts, he said "such decisions are taken after
giving due consideration to the opinions of the experts as well as
other issues."
</P>
<P>
According to the Press Trust of India (PTI), Vajpayee said it
was difficult to fix a time frame for accomplishing the on-going
military operations along the LoC, the de facto border between the
two antagonistic neighbors.
</P>
<P>
However, Indian Home Minister L. K. Advani said Wednesday he
was confident that the "Intruders" from Pakistan would be
completely evicted by the winter when the fighting must be stopped
because of the harsh weather condition in the area.
</P>
<P>
Advani reportedly said in Kargil, the Himalayan flashpoint
where the current crisis began, that the restrained approach taken
by the Indian government about not crossing the LoC had given the
country decided advantages.
</P>
<P>
"I don't see any radical change in the situation. We will be
able to foil this aggression completely and hold general elections
in time," he was quoted by PTI as saying. India's general
elections are scheduled for the coming September.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said the entire area would be soon cleared of
intruders with the steady progress in Kargil by Indian troops.
</P>
<P>
On his talks with former Pakistani foreign secretary Niaz Naik
last weekend in New Delhi, Vajpayee reiterated that there could be
no talks with Pakistan until the latter withdraws it troops from
Kargil.
</P>
<P>
He refused to comment on a report carried by the media both in
India and Pakistan that India had sent an emissary to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a senior Pakistani official as saying on
Tuesday that a joint secretary in the External Affairs Ministry in
charge of India, Pakistan and Afghanistan affairs and R. K.
Mishra, editor of the Observer of Business and Politics, had
visited the Pakistani border city of Lahore as an Indian emissary
11 days ago and met Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and Foreign
Secretary Shamshad Ahmad.
</P>
<P>
In return, Pakistan sent Naik to New Delhi last Saturday for a
day-long unannounced visit, the report said.
</P>
<P>
At a daily news briefing Wednesday, an External Affairs
Ministry spokesman evaded a direct response to the question,
saying only that it was part of "normal course of duties" that
they travel to countries they deal with.
</P>
<P>
The latest developments in the diplomatic front showed that,
due to economic and political conditions on both sides, and
especially international pressure to end the current conflict
through talks and other peaceful means, the fighting in Kashmir
seems unlikely to be further escalated into an all-out war between
India and Pakistan, observers said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said India was awaiting a response from Pakistan
on its demand that Islamabad withdraw its troops immediately from
Kargil.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that the directors general of military operations
of India and Pakistan were in touch but had not discussed any
proposal for de-escalation of tension in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the British Broadcasting Corporation
(BBC), Naik said the two directors could meet shortly to discuss
withdrawal of "intruders" from the Indian side of the LoC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
