<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-President Hu Jintao Meets Hong Kong SAR Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao
said here Wednesday that it is in the fundamental interests of the
six million Hong Kong people to maintain Hong Kong's prosperity
and stability.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with principal officials of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) at the Government House here late
Wednesday afternoon, the vice-president stressed that social
stability is the key to Hong Kong's prosperity and development and
that economic prosperity can ensure long-term stability.
</P>
<P>
Hu noted that maintaining Hong Kong's prosperity and stability
should always be the focal point in implementing the "one country,
two systems" policy and the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Hu conveyed the best regards and wishes from President Jiang
Zemin and the central government to the SAR officials present,
including Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa, senior government
officials, members of the Executive Council and leaders of the
legislative and judicial bodies.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president spoke highly of the work of the SAR
government, saying that the SAR government has administered Hong
Kong effectively and that the rights and freedoms of Hong Kong
residents have been fully protected.
</P>
<P>
People can see that the central government is firm in
implementing the policy of "one country, two systems," "Hong Kong
people governing Hong Kong" and a high degree of autonomy, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong maintains its status as a free port and
an international financial, trade and aviation center, that Hong
Kong's business environment remains one of the best in the world
and that its social and economic systems and the way of living
remain unchanged while the laws remain basically intact.
</P>
<P>
All this testifies to the vitality and correctness of the "one
country, two systems" policy, the wisdom and capability of the SAR
government led by Mr. Tung Chee Hwa to cope with the complex
situation, and the ability of the Hong Kong people to manage the
city, he said.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president noted that the practice of "one country, two
systems," "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" and a high degree
of autonomy is unprecedented and it is inevitable for some new
situations and new problems to crop up. Both the central
government and the SAR government should sum up experience from
time to time for new progress in the course of practice.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the recent interpretation of some provisions of the
Basic Law by the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress (NPC) in accordance with the Constitution, Hu said the
interpretation does not affect the Hong Kong SAR's independent
judicial power and power of final adjudication, but safeguards
Hong Kong's rule of law.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it is a consistent stand of the NPC and the
central government to safeguard Hong Kong's rule of law and that
such a stand will not change in the future.
</P>
<P>
Hu also praised Hong Kong's civil servants and legislative and
judicial staff for their contributions to Hong Kong's prosperity
and stability since its return to China by faithfully carrying out
their duties and ensuring the normal operations of various
institutions and the normal life of the Hong Kong residents.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the civil servants and legislative
and judicial staff will continue to support the work of the chief
executive and turn Hong Kong into a much better place in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Hu attended a dinner hosted by the SAR
government.
</P>
<P>
Among those present at the meeting and the dinner were Liao Hui,
director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the State
Council; Chen Fujin, deputy director of the General Office under
the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China; and Jiang
Enzhu, director of the Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch.
</P>
<P>
Hu came to Hong Kong from Shenzhen Tuesday to attend the
unveiling ceremony of the Reunification Monument on the second
anniversary of Hong Kong's return to China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
