<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Visitor Arrivals in Singapore Continue to Rise in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Visitor arrivals in Singapore
totaled 558,291 in May 1999, registering a year-on-year increase
of 1.8 percent largely fueled by a 4.2 percent growth in arrivals
from Asia, according to figures released Wednesday by Singapore
tourism Board (STB).
</P>
<P>
The swelled number of foreign visitors to Singapore in May
brought the total visitor arrivals in Singapore from January to
May this Year to 2,750,814, up 7.2 percent compared to the same
period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The number of visitors from Africa and Oceania continued to
grow by 13.6 and 0.5 percent respectively while arrivals from
America and Europe sank by 9.9 and 6.0 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Visitor arrivals from ASEAN totaled 218,609 in May, a 2.7
percent rise over the same period last year with visitors from
Thailand up 21.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Holiday arrivals from China rose by a robust 70.7 percent
year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
The economic recovery in South Korea generated 201.2 percent
more visitors to Singapore in May over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Among Singapore's 12 largest visitor-generating markets, half
of them registered a negative year-on-year growth.
</P>
<P>
Visitor arrivals from Japan, Malaysia and Britain also
registered negative growth in May this year ranging from 0.4 to
3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition to South Korea, China and Thailand, the numbers of
visitors from India, Indonesia and Australia picked up by 16.8,
0.7 and 0.3 percent respectively over a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
