<HEADLINE> Highlights of Today's Diplomatic News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
diplomatic news released by Xinhua today:
</P>
<P>
Sino-Japanese Exchange in Trade Unions
</P>
<P>
Wei Jianxing, chairman of the All-China Federation of Trade
Unions, said here today that the substantive exchange between
Chinese and Japanese trade unions has increased mutual
understanding and reinforced bilateral cooperation in the work of
trade unions.
</P>
<P>
Wei, also a member of the Political Bureau Standing Committee
of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China, made the
remarks during a meeting with a delegation from Japan's
International Labor Foundation headed by its president Shimitsu
Haruki.
</P>
<P>
Chinese, Cambodian FMs Discuss Ties
</P>
<P>
China has always maintained that the Khmer Rouge issue is part
of Cambodia's internal affairs, and it believes that the Cambodian
government and people can independently make judgments and
decisions to properly settle all such internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan made the remarks today in talks
with Hor Nam Hong, Cambodia's senior minister and minister of
foreign affairs and international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Hor Nam Hong stressed that it is imperative for the Cambodian
government and people to independently settle the issue.
</P>
<P>
Chinese, Togolese Defense Ministers Confer
</P>
<P>
Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian, in talks with Togo's
Defense Minister Assani Tidjani today, said that bilateral ties
have developed continuously since the establishment of diplomatic
relations between the two countries, and both sides have pursued
effective cooperation in political, economic, military, cultural
and other areas.
</P>
<P>
Chi, also vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission and
state councilor, thanked the Togolese government for its adherence
to the "one China" stance and consistent support in the human
rights issue.
</P>
<P>
Military Goodwill Delegation Returns to Beijing
</P>
<P>
A delegation of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA), led
by Li Jinai, political commissar of the PLA General Armament
Department, returned to Beijing today after a visit to Pakistan,
Bangladesh, Nepal and Myanmar.  
