<HEADLINE> Shas' Sages Endorse Joining Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Council of Torah Sages of
Israeli Shas Party has agreed in principle to join the incoming
coalition government to be headed by Prime Minister-elect Ehud
Barak, Shas announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The council, headed by Shas spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia
Yosef, has approved the coalition agreement at its Wednesday
afternoon meeting, but also asked Shas negotiators to settle the
issue of which party will take Religious Affairs Ministry before
signing it with One Israel under Barak, the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
The Shas negotiators have informed Barak of the council's
decision and requested Barak to give Shas more time to solve the
postship issue with the National Religious Party (NRP), which also
want to have this portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Sources from One Israel said that the two parties could reach
an agreement on the issue soon, with Shas taking the minister
portfolio while NRP getting its deputy.
</P>
<P>
Shas considers the Religious Affairs Ministry to be the fourth
ministry it is eligible to receive according to its Knesset
(parliament) seats and it should garner most posts in the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Shas won 17 seats in the 120-member knesset during the May 17
elections, becoming the third largest party in the legislature
just behind One Israel and Likud.
</P>
<P>
Among the potential coalition partners, only the Center Party
headed by former Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai has not made
final decision whether to join the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai has asked for another meeting later Wednesday with
Barak to thresh out whether the party could get two ministerial
portfolios.
</P>
<P>
One Israel has already signed coalition agreements with
Meretz, Yisrael Ba'aliya and the NRP. The United Torah Judaism
also struck its agreement with One Israel, deciding to support
the coalition government from the outside.
</P>
<P>
With the participation of Shas and the Center Party, Barak
could have a broad-based coalition with at least 75 Knesset
seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
