<HEADLINE> Optimism on Sino-U.S. Relations: Interview (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Twenty five years ago, John Holden,
who currently serves as president of the National Committee on
United States-China Relations, was known by local people as He
Liqiang during his first visit to Beijing. Now, Holden's Chinese
friends can call him "President He" in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
"I feel comfortable with and like the 'President He' title, and
I believe that it is easy for the people of our two countries to
make friends," Holden said in an interview with Xinhua before
leaving for home today.
</P>
<P>
There have been good exchanges between the two peoples, and
this is an important basis for bilateral relationships, said
Holden, who arrived in Beijing last Friday as a guest of the
Chinese People's Institute of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
