<HEADLINE> Optimism on Sino-U.S. Relations: Interview (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the visit, Holden met with senior officials of the
Chinese Foreign Ministry, the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation, and some other departments.
</P>
<P>
Holden, who served as president of the National Committee on
United States-China Relations last September, used to be a
businessman engaged in trade with China for years. He is also
known as an Old China Hand.
</P>
<P>
"My current China trip played its role in promoting mutual
understanding between the two sides," he said.
</P>
<P>
The National Committee on United States-China Relations,
established in 1966, consists of scholars on China issues and
representatives from business, labor trade unions, religion and
non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
As an unofficial organization, the National Committee on United
States-China Relations has made positive efforts to promote mutual
understanding between the people of the two countries and push
forward the improvement and development of Sino-U.S. relations. (
more)
