<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Optimism on Sino-U.S. Relations: Interview (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a leader of the committee, Holden has closely followed the
development of Sino-U.S. relations and he, naturally, also has his
own point of view on them.
</P>
<P>
"The two countries have engaged in cooperation. I think that
the next step is to upgrade such cooperation as much as we
possibly can, because China's development accords with the
fundamental interests of the U.S.," he said, adding that the
United States should show its sincerity in this regard.
</P>
<P>
In terms of economic growth, he continued, the two countries
have a shared interest, explaining that China hopes to develop
itself, and China's development represents enormous business
opportunities for the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, the U.S. and China, both as permanent members of the
United Nations Security Council, shoulder important
responsibilities for world peace, stability and prosperity," he
said. He added that the two countries can further cooperate in
China's accession to the World Trade Organization, and in helping
solve the Korean peninsula and other South Asia issues.
</P>
<P>
With regard to problems in Sino-U.S. relationships, Holden said
that the political systems, histories and cultural backgrounds of
the two countries are widely divergent, and it is natural to have
differences on some issues. "That requires mutual understanding,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Holden wrote an article a month ago, pointing out that more and
more American political celebrities understand the importance of a
steady and stable Sino-U.S. relationship. He added that if the
United States could not reach common understanding -- that China's
success will serve U.S. interests -- mutual trust between the two
countries will be further damaged.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes that China and the United Stated, as two great
countries, will pursue cooperation in all areas to create a
peaceful and stable future.
</P>
<P>
"This is my biggest wish," Holden added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
