<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Centralizes Government Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The procurement of equipment and
supplies for China's government ministries and institutions is to
be centralized under the control of the Bureau of Government
Offices Administration (BGOA) and the new procedure is already
being tested for the purchase of cars, computers and refurbishment
projects.
</P>
<P>
In a circular released today, the BGOA under the State Council,
China's highest governing body, urged government ministries and
institutions to actively push ahead the program, which is still in
a trial stage.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau now requires those departments under the State
Council to file their procurement plans and needs for the coming
year in May and September, which will all be pooled.
</P>
<P>
A system of public tendering will be the major method of
placing government procurement orders. Other methods, however,
will include purchasing through negotiation or from single sources,
but all controlled by the Bureau.
</P>
<P>
In the circular, the Bureau has listed those items which have
to be officially approved such as autos, boilers, elevators,
computers and peripheral equipment, copying and fax machines, air
conditioners, office furniture, refurbishing projects valued above
500,000 yuan, receptions for large-scale meetings and auto
insurance and repairs.
</P>
<P>
Government departments can only buy the goods and services
listed with BGOA approval. For those items not listed, the BGOA
still insists that they must be procured using government
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
The BGOA has set up a joint working and action group with the
State Development Planning Commission, the Ministry of Finance,
the Ministry of Construction and the Ministry of Supervision to
supervise the procurement activities of all ministries and
government institution to try and rein in the misappropriation of
funds and corrupt practices.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau stresses that all government procurement should be
made in an open, fair and justifiable manner. It should guarantee
quality of goods and services and place importance on efficiency.
</P>
<P>
It reveals that it will extend its scope in supervising and
controlling government procurement step by step, gradually
expanding to cover more goods and services.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wimbledon Tennis Results </HEADLINE>
