<HEADLINE> Southwest China Bids Farewell to Steam-Engine Locomotives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China ended its long
history of using steam-engine locomotives on its railway network
as the grand old steam loco numbered "3169" was withdrawn from
service today.
</P>
<P>
The "3169" has served for 19 years on the Chengdu-Chongqing
line which was first built in the mountainous area in 1950.
</P>
<P>
Steam-engine locomotives had been serving on most railways in
Southwest China until diesel-engine locomotives were introduced in
1965.
</P>
<P>
"Nearly all trains in this region are electricity-powered these
days, as a result of rapid social and economic development," said
Chen Qihua, director of the Chongqing Railway Administration.
</P>
<P>
"Trains in Southwest China are now traveling faster and faster,
" added Chen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
