<HEADLINE> No Slam-Dunk Favorite in Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- One of the most intriguing NBA
drafts in recent years will be showed tonight at the MCI Center.
</P>
<P>
With no clear-cut No. 1 pick like a Tim Duncan, several teams
will be looking to improve their position in the draft.
</P>
<P>
Atlanta traded veteran point guard Mookie Blaylock and the No.
21 pick to Golden State for the No. 10 pick, Bimbo Coles and Duane
Ferrell.
</P>
<P>
There are several players who added to the mystery of this
draft, including:
</P>
<P>
Lamar Odom, an early-entry candidate who unsuccessfully tried
to withdraw from the draft and return to college even though he
could be the first player selected. Jonathan Bender, jumping from
high school to the pros. Center Aleksandar Radojevic, a junior
college player who lost his NCAA eligibility because he was paid
for playing in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"There are a lot of good players in this draft," said Toronto
Raptors general manager Glen Grunwald, whose team has the N0.5 and
N0.12 selections.
</P>
<P>
"We'll get tow pretty good players. I don't think there are any
dominant players. I do think there are some players who will play
for a long time and help teams win games."
</P>
<P>
The Chicago Bulls, notoriously secretive about their intentions
in the draft, have the first pick. They have the league wondering
who they're going to take or if they will pull the trigger on any
of several trade offers.
</P>
<P>
"We just have to be prepared. We don't really know what Chicago
will do," said Bob Bass, vice president of basketball operations
for Charlotte, which has the No. 3 pick overall.
</P>
<P>
Chicago is one of six teams with multiple first-round picks.
</P>
</TEXT>
