<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Send Peace-keepers to Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- South Africa would send its
troops to the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) as
peace-keepers once a cease- fire was in place, President Thabo
Mbeki said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We'll have to send some South Africans to help contribute in
the peace making process," Mbeki told parliament in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
He said his government would do its best to ensure that any
troops were deployed legally and constitutionally.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from countries involved in the Congo (K) conflict are
meeting in Zambian capital Lusaka to try to put an end to the
11-month war.
</P>
<P>
Ministers from the involved countries and delegates from the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) have been locked in
talks in the past few days, which again aroused hopes for a
cease-fire in the vast central African country.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki praised South Africans and other African representatives
currently involved in the DRC peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"Progress has been made and I'm sure there'll be a resolution,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the South African Defense Ministry, the
time and size of such deployment have not been decided yet.
</P>
<P>
A Defense Ministry official said after Mbeki's announcement
that it could still take considerable time to finalize details for
the deployment of South African troops in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Colonel John Rolt said that the ministry was determining the
logistics for possible involvement in a DRC peace-keeping mission,
including timetables for the mission and the extent of the
deployment.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Patrick Lekota said Wednesday that South
African peace-keepers would be part of "a joint monitoring
commission", which would have a "non-combative capacity."
</P>
<P>
He said the commission would be established once the cease-fire
was in place and the size of it would be determined by the
Organization of African Unity (OAU). 
</P>
</TEXT>
