<HEADLINE> Israeli Defense Minister Criticized for Boycotting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Israel's outgoing Defense
Minister Moshe Arens was criticized Wednesday for his decision to
suspend Israel's participation in an international group that
monitors fighting in south Lebanon, Israeli radio reports said.
</P>
<P>
Former prime minister Shimon Peres, now the interim Knesset
(Parliament) speaker, dismissed the decision as "extreme,"
especially because it was made only days before Arens leaves the
government.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegation Tuesday boycotted a meeting of the
monitoring committee consisting of the United States, France,
Syria, Lebanon and Israel, which was formed in April 1996 after an
Israeli military offensive against Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The meeting had been scheduled to hear complaints by Lebanon
over the Israeli bombardment of Lebanon last week.
</P>
<P>
While delivering the boycott order, Arens said the Israeli
government will not attend further meetings of the monitoring
group as long as he is in charge of the Defense Ministry, saying
the "rules of the game" in Lebanon had changed.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister said the Lebanese Hezbollah militia has
been breaking the understanding reached after the 1996 cease-fire
which bars the two sides from attacks against or from civilian
targets.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, is leading a war of attrition to
oust Israeli troops from a border zone it carved out in south
Lebanon 14 years ago with a claimed aim of protecting Israel's
northern areas.
</P>
<P>
Israel unleashed a broad retaliatory air strike against
Lebanon last Thursday night after Katyusha rockets fired by
Hezbollah guerrillas killed two civilians in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Eight Lebanese civilians were killed and more than 60 others
wounded in the Israeli air strikes, which also caused severe
damage to infrastructure in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported Wednesday that senior military officials
were also angry at Arens' decision, saying it was "scandalous"
because the monitoring group is the only place where Israel can
sit together with Lebanon and its main power-broker Syria.
</P>
<P>
Arens admitted that his decision might not last beyond next
week, when Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak is supposed to have
presented a new government.
</P>
<P>
A moderate ex-army chief, Barak has pledged to withdraw
Israeli troops from south Lebanon within a year through
negotiations with Syria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
