<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hu Jintao Inspects Bank, Container Terminals in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao
inspected the Bank of China (BOC) Tower and the Kwai Chung
Container Terminals here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the company of Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) and Jiang Enzhu, director
of the Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch, Hu came to the Bank of
China Tower, the headquarters of the BOC Group in Hong Kong,
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
He mounted the 70-storey, 315-meter-high building, which is
located at Central of Hong Kong Island, to get a bird's-eye view
of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The BOC Group is one of the largest mainland-funded enterprises
in Hong Kong. In 1998, the BOC's overseas assets amounted to 900
billion U.S. dollars, making it the second largest banking group
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Hu then came to the Foreign Exchange Center on the eighth floor,
one of Hong Kong's major foreign exchange trading institutions.
</P>
<P>
He stopped from time to time to make inquiries to the staff
about the amount of currencies traded and the daily turnover in
the center.
</P>
<P>
Hu also made the round of the Business Hall on the second floor.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of China commenced its operation in Hong Kong in 1917
and became a note issuing bank in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon, Hu made a tour of Kwai Chung Container
Terminals in the company of Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa.
</P>
<P>
There are 19 routes connecting the terminals to major ports all
over the world. On the average, more than 100 ocean vessels come
in and go out of the terminals per day.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, one of the world's busiest container ports, handled
14.7 million TEUs (twenty-foot equivalent units) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
At a display room, HK Secretary for Economic Services Stephen
Ip briefed the visitors on the terminals.
</P>
<P>
Hu said that Hong Kong's shipping industry has great advantages
in the long term. There are not only geographical advantages but
also advantages in the area of services such as insurance and
arbitration, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong should make better use of these advantages and
enhance its competitiveness, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hu Jintao came to Hong Kong from Shenzhen Tuesday to attend the
unveiling ceremony of the Reunification Monument on the second
anniversary of Hong Kong's return to China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
