<HEADLINE> China Isn't Privatizing Nation's Assets: Jiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China's top leader has told the
Communist Party of China (CPC) members that the ongoing state-
owned enterprise reform featuring the establishment of share
holding companies doesn't mean that the country is carrying out
full blown privatization.
</P>
<P>
"Some comrades have misunderstood the situation, which has led
to certain deviations in the work in some localities," said Jiang
Zemin, general secretary of the CPC Central Committee, at a forum
held on June 28 to mark the 78th anniversary of the CPC's founding.
</P>
<P>
"China has state-owned assets worth over eight trillion, which
belong to the people and form an important economic foundation for
the country's socialist system," Jiang pointed out.
</P>
<P>
If a large amount of state-owned assets finally end up in the
pockets of a small number of people, then our socialist system
will lose its economic foundation, Jiang warned
</P>
<P>
"As a result, a correct understanding of and adherence to a
basic economic system in which public ownership constitutes the
main part and diversified forms of ownership of the economy enjoy
common develop, and a correct understanding and handling of the
relationship between the public and non-public sectors of the
economy is both a significant economic and political issue which
concerns the fate of the Party and the nation," Jiang emphasized.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to boost the state-owned sector, China, which is
in the primary stage of socialism, has started to experiment with
share holding and other forms of non-public ownership to
invigorate the whole economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
