<HEADLINE> Roundup: Australian Leaders Pay Tribute to Departing Fischer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Political leaders in Australia
Wednesday paid tribute to Tim Fischer who quit as the deputy prime
minister, trade minister and National Party leader, saying, "We'll
miss you, Tim."
</P>
<P>
In an emotional speech, Australian Prime Minister John Howard
described Fishcher as a political ally and warrior.
</P>
<P>
"No prime minister, no coalition leader, could have had a better
friend, a firmer ally or a more dependable colleague in difficult
times than I have had in you," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
"I will miss you, but I will always remember what a tremendous
political ally and warrior you have been."
</P>
<P>
During a special meeting of National Party MPs earlier
Wednesday, Fischer announced that he would quit on July 20 this
year to spend more time with his family.
</P>
<P>
There had been speculation that Fischer could quit because of
his son's mild autism, but he had given public assurances that he
would stay on in the parliament for the current three-year term,
which began late last year.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his understanding of Fischer's decision, Howard
said, "I know that the welfare of your family has been uppermost
in your mind in making the decision that you have made."
</P>
<P>
"You demonstrate that those personal things and those personal
associations and relationships are... infinitely more important
than any sort of glory, prestige, power or notoriety," he said.
</P>
<P>
A coalition between the National Party, which represents the
interest of Australian farmers, and the Liberal Party of Australia
led by Howard won last October's federal election to rule
Australia for a second three-year term.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Australian National Farmers' Federation President
Ian Donges said the nation's farmers would miss Fischer.
</P>
<P>
"Tim Fischer has been a champion of the Australian rural sector
since he was first elected in 1970 and the undoubted high point of
his career has been his last three years as Australia's trade
minister and deputy prime minister," Donges said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The farm sector will sorely miss Tim's consistent, passionate
and often colorful representation on our behalf," he said.
</P>
<P>
John Brown, Tourism Task Force chairman and a former labor
minister, said Fischer represented the industry with distinction
on his overseas trade missions.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that our industry was able to ride out the Asian
financial collapse with minimal damage is no small tribute to his
work."
</P>
<P>
Opposition trade spokesman Peter Cook said Fischer's
personality and energy had focused Australians on the importance
of promoting exports, winning access to new markets and creating
jobs in Australia.
</P>
<P>
"His enthusiasm for leading trade missions and developing new
markets for Australian exports is commendable."
</P>
<P>
Treasurer Peter Costello said Fischer was one of the great
characters of the parliament and of Australia.
</P>
<P>
"I had the honor to serve with him in opposition and in the
cabinet for over three years. He holds my great respect and
affection," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Australian Democrats leader Meg Lees said she was genuinely
saddened to learn of Fischer's resignation, despite their often
very different policy positions.
</P>
<P>
"Today, that is not important," Senator Lees said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"What is important is to recognize Tim's humanity, his
sincerity and his tireless work on behalf of his constituency --
Australia's farmers and those people living in regional and remote
Australia."
</P>
<P>
As this developed, the National Party decided to meet on
Thursday to elect a new leader.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Broadcasting Corporation reported that Fischer's
deputy in the party, John Anderson, has confirmed that he will run
for the vacancy left by Fischer, which brings with it the title of
deputy prime minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
