<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Pinpoint Age of Feathered Dinosaur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The age of the so called feathered
dinosaur, Sinosauropteryx, which is deemed the ancestor of modern
birds by many scientists, has been pinpointed at 125 million years
old by a team of international scientists.
</P>
<P>
The conclusion followed joint research by Swisher Carl from the
Berkeley Geochronology Center in the United States and Wang
Yuanqing along with other Chinese scientists from the Institute of
Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology under the Chinese
Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
Their paper making this claim will be published in the British
science journal, Nature, tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The research also indicates that the oldest flower and the
primitive mammal, Zhangheotherium, whose fossils were found in the
same area with that of feathered dinosaur, Beipiao in northeast
China's Liaoning Province, lived at the same time, the early
Cretaceous Period, instead of the late Jurassic Period of 144
million years ago as previously thought, said Xu Xing, one of the
authors of the paper.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of a large number of important fossils, including
Confuciusornis, Sinosauropteryx, Jeholodens, and the oldest flower,
in the same region in Liaoning Province, has drawn wide attention
from international academic fields.
</P>
<P>
However, scientists are divided over the age of the fossils
from the late Jurassic Period to the early Cretaceous Period. Most
of the papers published in academic journals are based on
biological stratigraphic study.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists collected turf samples from the fossil-
bearing stratum and sent the samples to the famous Berkeley
Geochronology Center in the United States for 40Ar/39Ar dating.
</P>
<P>
"This dating method is very accurate," said Xu.
</P>
<P>
He said that the dating shows that the famous fossils found in
Beipiao in Liaoning Province were younger than previously thought.
"We are forced to re-consider the complexity of biological
evolution."
</P>
<P>
"Clarifying the exact age of the fossils will provide new
insight into the study of the origin of birds, mammals and
flowering plants," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai 1st Quarter GDP Estimated to Rise 0.9 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product (GDP)
of Thailand in the first quarter of 1999 is expected to show a
growth of 0.9 percent year-on-year for the first time since the
country was hit by the economic crisis in mid-1997, an official
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sansern Wongcha-um, secretary-general of the National Economic
and Social Development Board (NESDB), said the figure was based on
joint estimates by the NESDB and the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's GDP began to drop in the second quarter of 1997 even
before the economic crisis broke out in July that year.
</P>
<P>
The downward trend of the country's GDP continued till the
fourth quarter of 1998. The bottom of the quarterly GDP decline
was seen in the second and third quarters of 1998, when the former
"tiger" economy experienced 12.3 and 12.5 percent contraction
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Sansern said the expected first-quarter GDP growth should be
attributed to higher production in both agriculture and
non-agriculture sectors.
</P>
<P>
The improvement of the economic situation in Thailand was
supported by growth from the supply side of the manufacturing
sector, with manufacturing output up 5.7 percent in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector's output in the first quarter rose 1.2
percent from the same period of last year while the services
sector also grew.
</P>
<P>
Sansern expected the GDP in the second quarter to show further
growth due to the government's economic stimulus measures.
Thailand has projected a 1-percent GDP growth for 1999.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the country's GDP contracted 8 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obasanjo Defends Appointment Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's President Olusegun
Obasanjo defended for the first time in the public Tuesday his
policies on appointments and retirements and that of the review
panels.
</P>
<P>
The president, speaking at the inauguration of the Council of
State in Abuja, said that merit and geographical spread were the
cardinal principles that guided the choice of ministers to be
sworn in Wednesday, reported The Guardian, a leading Nigerian
newspaper Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The president is under criticism recently that he has been
using the appointment and retirement of governmental officials to
marginalize the northerners, who had dominated the government for
quite a long time.
</P>
<P>
He urged state governors to "imbibe a collective sense of
purpose which will transcend narrow party loyalties and parochial
considerations."
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said the retirements in the armed forces were done
to protect democracy, re-orientate the armed forces and
subordinate them to civil authority.
</P>
<P>
"It has been observed that military officers who have held
political office find it difficult to fit into regimental duties
when they get back to the barracks the president said.
</P>
<P>
He added "their life-style has been found to breed discontent
among their colleagues who have not had the opportunity to hold
political office."
</P>
<P>
He explained that the advent of democratic governance after
prolonged military rule has given rise to euphoria mixed with
great expectations.
</P>
<P>
"There is an unequivocal consensus that in the past, we have
done very many things wrongly ... if we must avoid a repeat of
past errors, we should have patience to identify and correct these
errors."
</P>
<P>
The president who identified crisis of the economy as that of
poverty and mismanagement, said the situation has been compounded
by high rate of inflation, low capacity utilization in the
manufacturing sector, food insufficiency, unemployment and under
employment.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that steps have been taken to ensure availability
of fertilizers to farmers in the next couple of weeks saying "if
may be late for some but it will still be timely."
</P>
<P>
He added that the federal government decided to embark on the
rehabilitation project to stabilize power supply nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on National security, the president said the situation
in the Niger Delta area remained fragile and volatile, adding
that a team of military and mobile police personnel had been sent
there to man strategic locations, while the government was
developing a master-plan to guide the systematic development of
the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that a committee, made up of representatives of the
public and private sectors, had raised to help in formulating
policies on how best to move the economy forward.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the government would pursue the policy of
deregulation and privatization of some state-owned enterprises
"when it is judged that their performance would be enhanced
through such approach".
</P>
<P>
For foreigners seeking to do legitimate business in Nigeria, he
promised to provide a stable and secure environment, adding that
the government was keen to discuss all aspects of the country's
foreign debt with a view to achieving a level of relief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
