<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Sends Team for Investigation in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has sent
a task force to East Timor to investigate a stoning incident which
hurt seven people and damaged the office of the U.N. Mission in
East Timor (UNAMET) in Maliana subdistrict.
</P>
<P>
The task force, which consists of officers of the Foreign
Affairs Ministry and related ministries, will join the Task Force
for the Direct Ballot in East Timor and UNAMET chief Ian Martin in
visiting Maliana on Wednesday, Defense Minister Gen. Wiranto said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters here before attending a limited cabinet
meeting on politics and security, Wiranto said he will also ask
the Commission for Reconciliation and Stability to help solve the
incident fairly so that the direct ballot could be held on time.
</P>
<P>
The commission is composed of East Timorese, security officers,
members of the National Commission on Human Rights and U.N.
personnel.
</P>
<P>
"If the case could not be solved through dialogue, it will be
settled by the police," Wiranto said.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto, who is also chief of the Indonesian Armed Forces, said
the incident occurred after pro-integration supporters took refuge
at the UNAMET office in Maliana to avoid a confrontation with a
pro-independence group.
</P>
<P>
According to The Jakarta Post, a 100-strong group of
pro-Jakarta militiamen attacked an unarmed U.N. outpost in Maliana
on Tuesday. Seven people were injured during the incident,
including a U.N. officer.
</P>
<P>
The incident was the first reported case of violence against
the U.N. mission since it began work in East Timor last month
ahead of August's scheduled ballot to determine the future of the
territory.
</P>
<P>
The incident drew immediate reaction from U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan. A U.N. spokesman said in New York that Annan
"holds the Indonesian government accountable for allowing such an
attack to occur" and that any attack against U.N. personnel and
property was "unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Under a U.N.-brokered agreement with Portugal in May, Indonesia
agreed to hold the direct ballot in August this year.
</P>
<P>
The ballot will allow the territory's people to choose whether
their homeland should become an autonomous region within Indonesia
or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda's Tea Sector Set for Privatization by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government will
privatize its state-owned Tea Board by the year 2000, Rwandan
Prime Minister Pierre Celestin Rwigema announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Rwigema, the tea sector is of considerable
strategic importance in the country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 30 years, it has proved to be a consistently
growing asset for Rwanda's economy, creating 30,000 jobs, and
contributing to the stability of trade balance.
</P>
<P>
"Tea is second to Coffee as a foreign exchange contributor. It
makes up 71% of the total country exports and brought in 19
million U.S. dollars by the end of 1998," Rwigema underlined.
</P>
<P>
The government of Rwanda has today taken the decision to
privatize production units of Tea Board for development reasons,
the Rwanda News Agency quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The objective of this privatization is to mobilize and combine
private potential for share holding and management expertise by
injecting both foreign and local capital into the industry, so as
to allow the sector to maximize its output, thus contributing to
national development," he said.
</P>
<P>
As highlighted by the Rwandan Minister of Finance and Economic
Planning Donald Kaberuka, the tea sector in Rwanda was affected by
the 1994 genocide and civil war that led to a loss of 11,000 tons
between 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
According to the director of Tea Board, Jean Bosco Iyadema,
there are nine factories, with infrastructures and plantations,
and these include among others Mulindi in northeast, Kitabi, Mata,
Shagasha, and Gisakura in southwest, Gisovu in the west, Pfunda
and Rubaya in the northwest.
</P>
<P>
It is said that by the end of 1998, these factories produced 15
million kilograms more than any other year before, on 12,056
hectares for the whole country. The average yield last year was
1.04 tones per hectare.
</P>
<P>
The government proposes to privatize 60 to 80 % of her shares
for cash unit.
</P>
<P>
The privatization of 20 to 40 % of the remaining shares, which
the Tea Board will hold for a maximum duration of three years,
will be reserved for Rwandan investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
