<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Boosted by Trade Deficit Figures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
strengthened on Wednesday, bolstered by a better-than-expected May
trade deficit result.
</P>
<P>
The currency, languishing at the day's lows around 65.59 U.S.
cents, jumped to a high of 66.18 U.S. cents following the news.
</P>
<P>
It closed at 66.01 U.S. cents from 65.63 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speculation that Australia would face another severe blowout in
its monthly trade deficit reached a peak in offshore trading,
holding the currency down at around the mid-65 U.S. cents region
early in the day.
</P>
<P>
Also at the close, the Australian currency was trading at 63.86
euro cents from 63.58 Tuesday and 79.83 Japanese yen from 79.59.
</P>
