<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Fishermen Respect Fishing Ban in South China Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Fishermen in Macao have been
cooperative in the past month to comply with a fishing ban in the
South China Sea from June 1 to July 31, an official of the
Fishermen Association of Macao said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a circular issued by China's Ministry of
Agriculture in March this year, trawling and purse seine fishing
are banned in an area north to 12 degrees of north latitude,
including the Beibu Gulf.
</P>
<P>
"Macao fishermen give the consent that the fishing ban is
conducive to protecting fishing resources and safeguarding their
long-term interests," Fung Hee, director of the Fishermen
Association of Macao, told Xinhua on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he noted that many fishermen were not
accustomed to resting in the two months when they used to be busy
before.
</P>
<P>
"Macao fishermen expect that fishing departments in the
mainland areas of China can effectively carry out the ban so that
they will have good harvests in the future," Fung said.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the association, the population of
fishermen in Macao is estimated at about 4,000 who own some 450
fishing vessels.
</P>
<P>
Fung said the fishing ban has affected the income of fishermen
to some extent, but the association has received no reports of
difficult living. If there are such reports, the association will
make contact with relevant government departments.
</P>
<P>
Over the past month, the fishermen have used the period to
repair their boats and nets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
