<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- An Eva Airlines flight from Chinese
Taipei made an emergency landing Wednesday morning at the
Philippines' Ninoy Aquino International Airport (NAIA) after its
pilots discovered leaks in the aircraft's fuel line.
</P>
<P>
The airport authorities said no one among the 243 passengers
and crew members was hurt when Eva Air Flight BR 271 touched down
at the airport.
</P>
<P>
The commercial plane was still 550 miles (880 kilometers) away
from the NAIA when the passengers complained of pungent odor
pervading the cabin of the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
According to NAIA authority, the plane's pilot and a flight
officer traced the fuel leak to a broken fuel line leading to the
second engine of the three-engine McDonnel Douglas MD-11 jet.
</P>
<P>
They were forced to shut down the aircraft's tail engine in
order to keep the aircraft from burning.
</P>
<P>
They also radioed the Manila Control Tower for emergency
assistance once the aircraft landed at the airport.
</P>
<P>
As soon as the aircraft touched down safely, the pilots
immediately shut off the two other engines while the fire trucks
trailed the aircraft until it made a complete stop at the end of
the runway.
</P>
<P>
This was the third accident in three days at the airport. On
Monday, a Fedex cargo plane overshot an NAIA runway, forcing a
24-hour closure of the international runway.
</P>
<P>
On Monday night, an Air Philippines Boeing 737 jet broke loose
from a tug, causing one of its wings to hit several airport
apparatuses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
