<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese Minister of Trade and Economy Nasser Saidi
said that Israel's air strike on Lebanon's infrastructure would
have no serious effects on the country's economy or the summer
tourism season, the An Nahar newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference Monday to mark the launch of a
45-day shopping festival at east Lebanon's city of Baalbek, Saidi
said there was no en mass cancellation of hotel reservations by
summer vacationers from Gulf Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
"All the bookings, whether at hotels or airline companies are
to stay," he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister's remarks contrast with earlier reports from hotel
owners complaining about massive cancellation of bookings.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Morocco's citrus exports by the end of May amounted
to 573,000 tons, a drop of 3 percent compared to the previous
season.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the season, citrus exports volume was
estimated at 535,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic economic daily Alam Al Yom Wednesday quoted the
Moroccan Ministry of Agriculture, Rural Development and Fisheries
as saying that these exports included 223,000 tons "small size
fruits," and 350,000 tons of oranges.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT -- Several Arab Gulf states are expected to see their
state budget deficits down by at least 25 percent due to the
rise in oil prices to 10-12 U.S. dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
The Arab daily Al Hayat Wednesday quoted economic experts as
saying that the average petroleum price among the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) will exceed 14 dollars per barrel in 1999, leading
to an increase of 9 billion dollars over the anticipated petroleum
export revenues.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the GCC states which hold over 45 percent of world
oil reserves will expect a budget deficit of 22.5 percent this
year.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia will see a budget deficit of about 9 percent of
its gross domestic product (GDP), the highest since 1993 when it
hit 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The Syrian People's Council (parliament) Monday
passed a law stipulating a 21 percent tax exemption on the
production of cotton and cotton yarn in an effort to promote the
competitiveness of the country's textile sector in world markets.
</P>
<P>
The Arab daily Al Hayat Wednesday quoted Syrian economic
sources as saying that the new law will help cut production costs
of Syrian cotton which amounts to about one million tons a year.
</P>
<P>
Over 20 percent of Syria's 17 million population are engaged in
the field cotton production, and the area under cotton cultivation
is some 215,000 hectares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
