<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 49 Dead in Serious Floods in SW China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Serious floods in Sichuan Province,
southwest China, have killed 49 people in the last two months, the
vice-governor Jing Zhengshu announced today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the province's flood-control office show that
from late April to June 29, Sichuan experienced four major
rainfalls, with floods hitting 23 counties and affecting 830,000
people in terms of economic losses and damage to homes and farms.
</P>
<P>
The floods have seriously hit 67,000 hectares of crops,
destroyed 830 houses and led to the deaths of 49 people. Total
direct losses from the floods are estimated at some 200 million
yuan (about 24 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The water levels in Sichuan's major rivers have all risen to
different degrees, with some sections of the rivers reaching
record high water levels.
</P>
<P>
Some experts say that floods in these rivers may lead to the
rising of water levels in the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
It is still raining in the western part of Sichuan and the
local provincial government is making serious preparations for
fighting possibly more serious floods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
