<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Put East China Province on Full Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Jiangxi province in east China is
on full alert against floods expected to peak this evening
following days of heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
Local hydrologists report that floods will hit northern Jiangxi
's Changjiang river, a branch of the Yangtze river, at around 21:
00 pm. The flood level had already exceeded the warning mark by 3.
74 meters this afternoon and when it peaks is expected to push the
waters to 4.8 meters above the danger mark.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jingdezhen, a city for its Chinaware on the Yangtze
river, was flooded today.
</P>
<P>
Water levels at Boyang Lake, one of China's largest freshwater
lakes on the Yangtze river, are also approaching the warning stage,
with three hydrological stations between the lake and the Yangtze
river warning of flood peaks over the next 24 hours. And the flood
levels will continue to rise in the following days.
</P>
<P>
The weather forecast indicates more heavy rains over the next
few days. The provincial flood-control headquarters this morning
issued an emergency notice to step up preparations for severe
floods.
</P>
<P>
Top officials of the provincial government have moved into
Jingdezhen city to direct anti-flood efforts. And an emergency
meeting of city leaders has appealed to local people to give top
priority to the fight against floods so as to guarantee that not a
single dam collapses and not a single person dies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
