<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Rules Out Cabinet Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
said Wednesday that he has no intention of implementing a revamp
of his cabinet one year after assuming the highest post of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the president shared the credit of weathering the
currency crisis with the members of his "official family,"
particularly the country's economic managers who helped him set in
place measures to combat the regional financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview, the president said he could not have done
all that alone, especially "at a time when many of our neighbors
in Asia have been set back by the currency crisis."
</P>
<P>
He said there is no reason for him to implement a cabinet
revamp, adding that the members of his "official family" have been
doing so well in their duties in their respective departments.
</P>
<P>
He particularly lauded the contributions of his economic
managers -- Trade Secretary Jose Pardo, National Economic and
Development Authority Director-General Felipe Medalla, Budget
Secretary Benjamin Diokno and Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu.
</P>
<P>
"They are the ones who really helped me and who sacrificed so
we can attain economic recovery and overcome the crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he ruled out speculations about division and
rift among his cabinet members, adding that reports of
disagreements are just clear signs of transparency in his
government.
</P>
<P>
He said the differences of opinion only show that "there is
freedom to express their views in the cabinet." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
