<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Slams British-Dutch Draft Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 30 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi daily on Wednesday
slammed a draft resolution by Britain and the Netherlands recently
submitted to the U.N. Security Council on the Iraqi issue, as "a
virulent attempt to undermine Iraq's legitimate right."
</P>
<P>
Al-Thawra daily, organ of the ruling Baath party, said the
draft resolution is aimed at undermining Paragraph 22 of the
U.N. resolution 687 which requires the Security Council to lift
the sanctions after Iraq has fulfilled all its commitments.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the Netherlands recently proposed to the Security
Council that the U.N. sanctions on Iraq be suspended after Iraq
fully cooperates with an enlarged body of weapon inspectors, which
will replace the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) and carry out
more intrusive inspections on Iraq's banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
The daily said that the U.S. and British governments have never
been concerned with Iraq or the Iraqi people. "How could such
states try to present a draft resolution alleviating sufferings
of the Iraqi people?" inquired the daily.
</P>
<P>
It added that Iraq has the full right to reject such a
resolution and any similar one that deprives Iraq of its
legitimate demands and adds more conditions for lifting the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq also has the right to caution good-will individuals in
the Security Council not to fall in the Anglo-American trap and
get involved in approving or accepting the proposal.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed economic sanctions on Iraq
after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
