<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Readjusted Income Distribution Crucial for Expanding Demand (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A resurgence of China's weak
domestic market, a prerequisite for the nation's sustainable
economic growth, depends on readjusting income distribution in
order to raise the income level of Chinese citizens, according to
the Wednesday edition of Economic Daily.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper's weekly economic review cited one economist's
view that the gap between demand and supply stems from the
declining income expectancy linked with the rising cost of living
which demands increased spending to be fueled by higher incomes.
</P>
<P>
The income growth rate for Chinese citizens has slowed in
recent years. Disposable income for Chinese citizens grew 6.6
percent on an annual basis in 1998 after considering price factors,
with the rate for the early 1990s standing at 7.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, income and consumption discrepancies between urban
and rural residents have become more distinct, with the purchasing
power of low income families which account for the bulk of
potential consumption declining in spite of government efforts to
stimulate domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
The latest official statistics show a continuing decline in
retail prices in recent months due to soft sales. Nonetheless, the
country's economy has continued to grow smoothly during the period.
The May RPI (retail price index) dropped 1.3 percent on the April
level, with the total consumer goods retail sales growth dipping
by 0.4 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
