<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Readjusted Income Distribution Crucial for Expanding Demand (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Any continuance of the downward trend in consumption will
produce a negative impact on enterprises and sustainable national
economic growth, according the Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has responded by adopting a series of
measures to stimulate domestic demand, including intensified fixed-
asset investments, regulations favoring consumer credit and
several interest rate reductions.
</P>
<P>
However, the lagging income growth for the majority of Chinese
citizens has offset government efforts.
</P>
<P>
In addition, recent reform of the housing, healthcare, pension
and social security systems has placed a heavier burden on
citizens and prompted them to retain bank saving accounts in spite
of low interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The government must address the issue by initiating reform of
the distribution system, increasing salary levels for low income
workers and strengthening income tax levies, as well as developing
sound welfare and social security systems, according to the
article.
</P>
<P>
A substantial portion of salaries for workers and government
employees was previously applied to welfare benefits such as
housing and healthcare services. Today, however, they are
personally responsible for welfare benefits and thus income levels
should be raised accordingly.
</P>
<P>
The government should earmark a certain proportion of its
budget to ensure basic living standards for Chinese citizens,
particularly unemployed and retired people.
</P>
<P>
The article also called for improved income tax collections and
the introduction of new inheritance and gift taxes to help
facilitate the establishment of an efficient redistribution system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
