<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Samsung to Seek Court Receivership for Automaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 30 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Samsung Group announced
Wednesday that it will apply for court receivership for Samsung
Motors instead of selling it to Daewoo Group.
</P>
<P>
The group boss Lee Kun-hee said on Wednesday that he will sell
his personal four million shares at Samsung Life Insurance valued
around 2.8 trillion won (some 2.4 billion U.S. dollars) for
Samsung Motors to reduce debt burden on creditor banks,
subcontractors and subsidiary companies.
</P>
<P>
Samsung Life Insurance controls 35 percent of South Korean life
insurance market, whose assets hit 36.4 trillion won.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came six months after Samsung and Deawoo
failed to reach any agreement on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Samsung agreed to give its start-up automaking
unit to Daewoo Motors in exchange for Daewoo's Electronics as a
part of "big deal" proposed by the South Korean Government against
over expansion and redundant investments.
</P>
<P>
"We decided to end this now. We thought this would be the best
for the economy," said Samsung Motors Vice Chairman Lee Dae-won.
</P>
<P>
Samsung said it will immediately supply 600 billion won from
Lee Kun-hee's contribution to help ailing subcontractors.
</P>
<P>
Following Samsung's announcement, the South Korean government
said it may allow Samsung Life to go public within this year
rather than the initial schedule of the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Samsung Motors' debt will down to some two trillion won after
Lee's donation as the automaker needs 3.1 trillion won to repay
the debt.
</P>
<P>
The other 1.2 trillion of the automaker's total debt of 4.3
trillion won are loans from the group's financial units.
</P>
<P>
Samsung Motors' corporate value is estimated around 1.5
trillion won.
</P>
<P>
Lee's contribution will thus pay off all of the automaker's
debts with credit banks. Creditors will actually have nothing to
lose if Samsung Life's share value rises, said the automaker's
vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
It will take the receivership court three months to study
Samsung's application before endorsing the receivership and
appointing a manager to determine the automaker's future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
