<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists, Journalists to Leave for North Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A team made up of more than 120
scientists and journalists will leave for the North Pole tomorrow
as part of China's first scientific expedition to the remote polar
region.
</P>
<P>
Members of the team braved rain today to move equipment, food
and other cargoes onto the "Snow Dragon", an icebreaker that has
been used in several Antarctic expeditions in the past 15 years,
which is anchored in the dock in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Shaohong, captain of the ship, said all the preparation
work had been finished before 5:00 pm today.
</P>
<P>
A website, www.bjkk.com.cn, has been opened for those
interested in the expedition.
</P>
<P>
Chen Liqi, director of the polar region expedition office under
the State Oceanic Administration, said today on the ship that the
expedition will increase Chinese scientists' knowledge of the
mysterious Arctic region.
</P>
<P>
The scientists will study the effect of the North Pole on the
global climate, especially on that of China, the ecological system
in Arctic waters, and the atmosphere, geology, fishing, and marine
environment of the area.
</P>
<P>
The expedition will take more than two months, and the
scientists are expected to return home in late September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
