<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Council Urges Industrialized World to Do More Against Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Either we progress together or we sink together," Fulci warned.
"Unless we act swiftly to reverse the spread of abject poverty,
our world tomorrow will be much worse and the prosperity and
security of many will be put at risk."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a UN report said that over 1.5 billion people still
live on less than one U.S. dollar per day and the number of
absolute poor continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
There are close to one billion adult illiterates in the world,
most of whom are women, the report said. Three quarters of a
billion people have no access to health services. Malnutrition
affects over 800 million people. Many millions lack access to safe
water, and many millions more have a life expectancy of less than
40 years.
</P>
<P>
The greatest number of people below the poverty line live in
Asia, the report said, but the depth of poverty, which measures
how far incomes fall below the poverty line, is greater in sub-
Saharan Africa than any other region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
