<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transgenic Engineering Industry Center Set up in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China's first transgenic center
has been established by the Zhejiang Chaofan Transgenic
Engineering Company as part of a national effort to promote the
development and production of transgenic animals and related
products.
</P>
<P>
The company, jointly established by the national transgenic
sheep research team and east China's Zhejiang Province at a cost
of 47.7 million yuan, will concentrate on raising genetically
altered animals and manufacturing various drugs using the milk of
these animals, on the basis of technology developed by the
research team.
</P>
<P>
The team, consisting of Zeng Yitao and Huang Shuzhen and other
scientists from the Shanghai Institute of Medical Sciences and
Genetics, injected the human blood clotting agent Factor IX into a
zygote of a goat which was then transplanted into the womb of a
female goat, resulting in the first transgenic goat in China last
year. It later produced milk containing Factor IX.
</P>
<P>
The scientists then used a similar method on a cow by
transplanting embryos grown in test tubes out of zygotes with
human albumin genes into eight cows, three of which became
pregnant, one of which gave birth to a transgenic calf in February
this year.
</P>
<P>
Experts say these achievements will greatly benefit human
albumin drug production using genetically altered animal milk and
this is specially important for the safety of products derived
from human plasma.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Fiber Optical Cable Inaugurated in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 30 (Xinhua) -- One of the biggest fiber
optical projects in the region was inaugurated Wednesday in
Cambodia, greatly upgrading the country's existing
telecommunications network.
</P>
<P>
The inauguration ceremony held in the northern province of
Kompong Chhnang, about 70 kilometers from the capital, was
attended by Prime Minister Hun Sen, Post and Telecommunications
Minister So Khun, local authorities representatives, the German
ambassador, high-ranking officials from Germany as well as
representatives from Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The cable was donated by Germany and it costs about 10 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In his inauguration speech, Hun Sen thanked the German
government for its free assistance in modernizing the Cambodian
network.
</P>
<P>
He said, "All the projects built under the aid of the friendly
countries have played an important role in Cambodia's economic
development and its integration into the international community."
</P>
<P>
"As a country less developed in economy, we need to make even
more efforts to integrate ourselves into the world with higher
technology," said Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
The 608-kilometer-long cable will provide the foundation for
the rapid expansion of telecommunications in the country and grant
substantial savings for telephone users.
</P>
<P>
The project, linking the Cambodian-Thai border at Poipet to the
Cambodian-Vietnamese border at Bavet through Phnom Penh, the
Cambodian capital, is the first step toward creating an
information superhighway connecting the six countries bordering
the Mekong River -- China, Vietnam, Laos, Cambodia, Thailand and
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
"At present, only about one people among 100 Cambodians has a
telephone while there is a higher percentage in the capital at
more than 7 percent. By 2003, we will be able to see two people
among 100 will have telephone," Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
He added that 200 million U.S. dollars will be needed in
investment in this project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
