<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 5,000 Cultural Relics Unearthed in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Archaeologists have unearthed 5,
243 cultural relics with the completion of the first phase of the
excavation work on an ancient tomb complex dating to the Han
Dynasty (206-24 B.C.) in the eastern suburbs of Kunming, capital
of Yunnan Province in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
They excavated 524 tombs in an area covering over 16,000 square
meters between September 1998 and June 1999. The articles include
lacquered wood carvings and bronze cooking vessels, kettles and
weapons.
</P>
<P>
The discovery, which represents the largest group of ancient
tombs thus far discovered in the province, will provide valuable
clues for research into the province's history and ancient society.
</P>
</TEXT>
