<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Partnership Essential for Labor Training: Singapore Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Minister of Manpower
Lee Boon Yang Wednesday stressed that the tripartite partnership
between employees, employers and the government is essential for
the training and development of the work force.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the International Labor Organization
(ILO) Asian and Pacific Tripartite Consultative Meeting here, Lee
said the effectiveness of human resources development (HRD) and
training efforts hinges very much on partnership and shared
commitment of employees, employers and the government.
</P>
<P>
He said effective HRD programs would require employers to
invest in training and skill upgrading that go beyond meeting the
requirements of the present jobs and employers must prepare
workers for changes in technology and the way in which a company
does its business.
</P>
<P>
Citing skill upgrading as the worker's guarantee for
employability, Lee said employees' active participation in
learning and re-learning would sharpen their competency and
adaptability to new and higher-value-added jobs in a rapidly
changing business environment.
</P>
<P>
Lee also rests special responsibility on the government, saying
governments have a special responsibility to invest and equip the
work force with basic education that is essential for the
acquisition of new skills to keep pace with technological changes.
</P>
<P>
"Governments must promote the concept of life-learning and
constant refreshing of every worker's stock of skills and
knowledge," he added.
</P>
<P>
He told the meeting that as a result of tripartite efforts,
Singapore spent more than 258 million Singapore dollars (about 152
million U.S. dollars) on workers' skills development last year and
 more than 20,000 workers from 249 companies from many different
sectors are committed to training under the Skills Redevelopment
Program.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that his country will launch a strategic manpower
blueprint, known as "Manpower 21," next month with its strategic
thrust to be taken for the creation of a national system of
life-learning for workers.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is held by the ILO in collaboration with
Singapore's Ministry of Manpower to serve as a forum to review
country situations and exchange experiences on HRD and training
especially in the context of increasing globalization.
</P>
<P>
A total of 45 participants including representatives of the
government, employees and employers from 14 countries in the
Asian-Pacific region are attending the seminar which will last
until July 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
