<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Deputy PM Quits for Family Reasons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Australian Deputy Prime Minister
and Trade Minister Tim Fischer announced Wednesday that he would
quit from July 20 this year in order to spend more time with his
family.
</P>
<P>
In a recorded message broadcast by the Australian Broadcasting
Corporation (ABC), Fischer also said he would resign as leader of
the National Party of Australia, the minor partner of Australia's
ruling coalition under the leadership of Prime Minister John
Howard.
</P>
<P>
Howard leaves on Monday for a two-week trip to Japan and the
United States and Fischer will be acting prime minister until July
20.
</P>
<P>
There had been speculation that Fischer could quit because of
his son's mild autism, but he had given public assurances that he
would stay on in the parliament for the current three-year term,
which began late last year.
</P>
<P>
Fischer announced his resignation earlier Wednesday during a
special meeting of National Party MPs he called to inform them of
his decision.
</P>
<P>
In a speech Wednesday on Fischer's resignation decision, Howard
said he will miss Fischer for his loyalty to the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said his party will hold a meeting Thursday to elect
his successor as new party leader.
</P>
<P>
The ABC reported that Fischer's deputy John Anderson has
confirmed that he will run for the vacancy left by Fischer, which
brings with it the title of deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
A coalition between the National Party, which represents the
interest of Australian farmers, and the Liberal Party of Australia
led by the prime minister won last October's federal election to
rule Australia for a second three-year term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
