<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Standardize Production of Traditional Chinese Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China is to introduce a quality
management system to put an end to the historical lack of
standards and norms which have affected the production of
traditional Chinese medicines for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
The aim is to ensure the production of Chinese herbal medicine
in a scientific and modern way so that they will also be accepted
by people of other nations.
</P>
<P>
China is abundant in plant resources for medicine, with an
estimated 10,000 varieties. It also has a rich variety of minerals
that can be used as raw drugs.
</P>
<P>
However, although Chinese herbal medicine has a history of
thousands of years in China, it accounts for only three to five
percent of the world herbal medicine market which stands at 16
billion U.S. dollars a year. The remainder of the market is shared
by Japan, India, Thailand and The Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
China's Ministry of Science and Technology has already decided
to launch very soon a project to modernize the traditional Chinese
medicine sector.
</P>
<P>
So far, 124 countries worldwide have established various kinds
of institutions related to traditional Chinese medicine and more
than 9,000 people come to China to receive training each year.
</P>
<P>
France, for example, has 2,800 clinics offering traditional
Chinese medicine treatment and the country currently consumes 43,
000 tons of such medicines every year.
</P>
<P>
It has also been learned that many countries have begun
stepping up their research into Chinese herbal medicines over the
past few years and Japan has more than 20,000 kinds of Chinese
preparations.
</P>
<P>
Now the traditional Chinese medicines produced by two
pharmaceutical plants in Tianjin and Shanghai have passed the
authentication of the U.S. Food and Drug Administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expecting Stable Tea Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China's tea output for this year
is expected to reach 665,000 tons, equal to that of last year or
even slightly higher, according to forecasts from the Ministry of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
An official from the plantation department of the ministry
noted that the weather this year is favorable for tea growing. As
a result of that, the quality of Spring tea is better than last
year. Meanwhile, Summer and Autumn tea is growing well.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that the output of good quality and well-known tea
products, which reached 116,000 tons last year or 17 percent of
the total tea harvest, is expected to go higher this year and will
nudge the market price lower.
</P>
<P>
China known as the "Home of Tea" is one of the major tea
exporters in the world. Its tea production, however, fell into the
doldrums between 1993 to 1995 due to a downturn in the
international tea market and rising production costs at home. The
output at one point dropped to 400,000 tons from a high of 800,000
tons.
</P>
<P>
The sector is now coming out of shadows by restructuring its
product mix. China's tea plantation acreage now has increased to
760,000 ha. and domestic sales last year reached 395,000 tons
earning 7.1 billion yuan (about 865 million US dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
