<HEADLINE> Female Drug Trafficker Executed In Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 30 (Xinhua -- A female drug dealer was executed
in the city of Anshan, one of China's steel production bases in
the northeastern province of Liaoning, over the weekend, local
authorities announced today.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Xia, 36, was convicted of purchasing heroin from the
border area of southwest China's Yunnan Province in March of 1997,
and, with the assistance of her husband, selling the drug to
addicts in Anshan for a profit of 6,000 yuan (about 750 US dollars)
. The Anshan police also seized 590.2 grams of heroin from Zhou's
house while carrying out the arrest.
</P>
<P>
According to police investigations, Zhou, a jobless person from
the Tiedong District of Anshan, became addicted to drugs after
encouragement by her husband and the main purpose of her drug
dealing was to finance her own habit.
</P>
<P>
Zhou was sentenced to death by a local court for transporting
and trading in drugs, and the death penalty was recently confirmed
by the Supreme People's Court in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Zhou's husband, who was charged with trading in drugs, was also
sentenced to death in a first instance trial, but is still waiting
for the final judgment of the supreme court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
