<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stresses Developing Nations' Role in WTO Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China stressed the role of
developing countries in the forthcoming global trade negotiations
at the end of the trade ministers' meeting of the Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC), which concluded here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day meeting, trade ministers or representatives of
the APEC's 21 economies gave their top priority to the new round
of global trade negotiations to be launched by the World Trade
Organization (WTO) at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Minister of Trade and Economic Cooperation Long
Yongtu said China hopes that the contents and outcomes of the new
round of WTO negotiations will help set up a fairer and more open
trade system.
</P>
<P>
Although the world economy has benefited from trade and
investment liberalization in the past two decades, the benefits of
different countries are greatly unbalanced, he said.
</P>
<P>
"As a matter of fact, the gap between economies is widening
instead of narrowing and many developing economies have not
achieved the expected rapid growth. The least developed countries
are still increasing.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the new round of WTO negotiations should not only
be aimed at promoting the global trade growth and the world
economic development in general, but also it should fully consider
the demands and interests of the developing economies, so that
they can benefit more from the multilateral trade system," Long
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Only in this way, he continued, the new round of WTO
negotiations will win the broad support of and active
participation by developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Long noted that the economic growth of developing countries and
their support and participation are crucial to the success of the
new round of WTO negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the new round of WTO negotiations will contribute
to the stability of the world economy and its steady growth.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Malaysia, the Republic of Korea, Japan and
New Zealand were of the view that the agenda of the new round of
WTO negotiations should take the interests of all parties into
account.
</P>
<P>
They said they would be glad to see China and other countries
and regions who are applying for membership of the WTO join the
organization as soon as possible. They noted that without China's
participation, the new round of WTO negotiations will be
impossible to achieve its complete success.
</P>
<P>
Many representatives noted that developing countries would
suffer from long-term effects of the economic crisis and that they
should not participate in the new round of WTO negotiations while
carrying on their crisis burdens. They also called on other
countries to help developing countries completely get rid of the
economic crisis quickly.
</P>
<P>
The representatives urged the informal meeting of APEC leaders,
which will be held here in September, to make suggestions
concerning the agenda and direction of the new round of WTO
negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
