<HEADLINE> Foreign Capital Flow Up in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investments
maintained a 21 percent increase over the past four years with
1998/1999 fiscal year topping 230 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's Monitor daily said that total foreign direst
investment from January 1995 to January 1998 for Uganda is 422
million dollars, much higher than the reportedly 65 million
dollars for Kenya over the same period.
</P>
<P>
In the background to the Budget 1999/2000, the Ministry of
Finance said the investment as a percentage of gross domestic
product (GDP) is projected at 3.5 percent during 1998/1999
financial year ending by the end of June, up from 3.1 percent of
GDP last year.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the ministry show that during financial year
1996/1997, foreign direct investment amounted to 160 million
dollars, nearly 40 million dollars more than that registered in
the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The positive trend in the foreign direct investment inflow is
attributed to strong government commitment to sound economic
policies, particularly fiscal discipline, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
