<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2.5 Million Children Compelled to Work in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- It is estimated that some 2.5
million children are compelled to work to earn a living in
Indonesia and some 2,000 of them are known to be employed at
high-risk places, Manpower Minister Fahmi Idris said.
</P>
<P>
Children could work due to economic reasons, but their working
hours should be limited to three hours a day only so that they can
still go to school after work, Antara News Agency Wednesday quoted
Fahmi as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister said at the launching ceremony of a
program on overcoming child labor problems in Indonesia here
Tuesday, that the government cannot tolerate children working at
places entailing high risks to their safety.
</P>
<P>
He said child labor is a problem which cannot be solved through
raids but must be solved comprehensively by providing employment
to families.
</P>
<P>
Fahmi admitted that following the deepening of the economic
crisis that has swept the whole country, the number of children
compelled to earn a living is showing an upward tendency.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, child labor in Indonesia was estimated to stand at
some 2.4 million, but in 1995 the number was down to 1.7 million,
he said, adding that in 1998, however, the number went up again to
2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion the minister also witnessed the signing of a
cooperation agreement on overcoming child labor problems between
the International Labor Organization (ILO) and the Indonesian
government.
</P>
<P>
ILO has made available 1.2 million U.S. dollars in aid to
support activities carried out under the cooperation scheme.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
