<HEADLINE> Visa Requirement Waiver Drawing More Tourists to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government's removal of
 visa requirements for tourists from some European and American
countries is paying dividends, the Kenya Tourist Board (KTB) has
announced.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Wednesday quoted KTB
chairman Eliud Mahihu as saying that as a result of the waiver,
the first batch of 371 Belgian tourists arrived in Kenya's
capital Nairobi Monday night aboard a chartered plane.
</P>
<P>
The tourists were welcomed by Assistant Minister for Tourism
Tola Kofa and acting mayor Abdulatif Ali of the Indian port city
Mombasa, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
Other 3,000 tourists from Belgium, two times more than those
from the country last year, will arrive in the next three months.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government last month waived visa requirements for
15 countries including Britain, France, Belgium, Germany, Italy,
the Untied States, Spain, Canada and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
KTB chairman Muhidu also urged government to consider waiving
visa requirements on Nordic countries to invigorate tourism
sector, which is Kenya's major foreign currency earner and has
been in a slump in recent years.  
</P>
