<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Deputy PM Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Australian Deputy Prime Minister
and Trade Minister Tim Fischer quit his job Wednesday, the office
of Australian Prime Minister John Howard has confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Fischer also resigned as leader of the National Party of
Australia during Wednesday's special meeting of National Party MPs
he called to inform them of his decision.
</P>
<P>
However he would stay on as a government backbencher.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the prime minister did not say whether Howard
will accept Fischer's resignation, but added that the prime
minister's comment will come very soon as he is making a speech in
the Australian Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Fischer's office was unattended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Broadcasting Corporation reported that John
Anderson, deputy leader of the National Party of Australia, has
confirmed that he will run for the vacancy left by Fischer as
leader of the party.
</P>
<P>
The coalition between the National Party of Australia, which
represents the interest of Australian farmers, and the Liberal
Party of Australia under the leadership of the prime minister was
re-elected last October to rule Australia for a second three-year
term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
