<HEADLINE> Successful Transplant of Unfrozen Test-Tube Embryo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A hospital in Hangzhou, capital
of east China's Zhejiang Province, has successfully transplanted
an unfrozen test-tube embryo into a woman's womb.
</P>
<P>
A recent examination shows that the embryo, which had been
frozen for 15 months, is growing well in the womb.
</P>
<P>
The woman, who has only given her surname Liu, had been unable
to conceive during her eight year marriage and sought help from
the Zhejiang Women's Hospital in 1997.
</P>
<P>
After finding an obstruction in both her fallopian tubes,
doctors took ova from her and bred several embryos in a test-tube.
They then transplanted one of the embryos into her womb, while
freezing the others in the hospital, with Liu's approval.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, Liu had a miscarriage when she was five months
pregnant. In March this year, she went to the hospital again and
underwent the transplant of an unfrozen embryo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
