<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yellow River Tributary Remains Dry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADOI (QINGHAI), JUNE 30 (Xinhua) -- The mainstream of the
Yellow River at its source in Qinghai Province, northwest China,
has remained dry for eight months.
</P>
<P>
Gengque, the magistrate of Madoi County in Qinghai Province,
noted that the mainstream had never before remained dry from one
year to another.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River is 5,464 km long, running through nine
provinces and autonomous regions before emptying into the Yellow
Sea. Headwaters initially flow into Zhaling Lake and on to Eling
Lake before surging downstream to the middle and lower reaches of
the river.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey revealed that the May water level in Eling was
one meter below the 4,268 meter level in 1993, with the water flow
rate falling from 7.8 cu.m. per second to 2.7 cu.m. per second.
</P>
<P>
Madoi County, an area covering 25,000 sq.km., originally had 4,
077 lakes covering more than one sq.km. each. However, over 2,000
smaller lakes which used to dot grasslands and river valleys no
longer exist.
</P>
<P>
Gengque attributed the phenomenon to successive droughts, the
shrinkage of grasslands and the deteriorating environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Divers Complete Clean Sweep of Golds at Swedish Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese divers completed a clean
sweep of all the golds offered at the Swedish Cup international
diving meet after winning the women's 3-meter board and men's
platform in Ronneby, Sweden, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Guo Jingjing snatched the women's 3-meter board title with
relative ease by scoring 566.80 points, almost 40 points ahead of
second placed Swede Anna Lindberg at 528.25 points.
</P>
<P>
Another Chinese Zhang Jing was third only 2.55 points short of
Lindberg.
</P>
<P>
In men's platform, Tian Liang also won with a large margin. He
collected 686.05 points ahead of runner-up David Pichler at 591.75.
The bronze medal went to Mexico's Eduaro Rueda who had 586.95.
</P>
<P>
In the first two days of the three-day event, Xiong Ni took the
men's three meters board while Li Na carried home the women's
platform gold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
