<HEADLINE> Australian Deputy PM Resigns Citing Family Reasons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Australian Deputy Prime Minister
and Trade Minister Tim Fischer quit his job Wednesday, citing
family reasons for his shocking resignation.
</P>
<P>
In a recorded message broadcast by the Australian Broadcasting
Corporation (ABC), Fischer, who also resigned as leader of the
National Party of Australia, cited family difficulty behind the
reasons he quit.
</P>
<P>
There had been speculation that Fischer could resign because of
his son's mild autism, but he had given public assurances that he
would stay on in the parliament for the current three-year term,
which began late last year, the Australian Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
Fischer announced his resignation earlier Wednesday during a
special meeting of National Party MPs he called to inform them of
his decision.
</P>
<P>
In response to the resignation decision of his coalition
partner, Australian Prime Minister John Howard said he will miss
Fischer for his loyalty.
</P>
<P>
The ABC also reported that John Anderson, deputy leader of the
National Party of Australia, has confirmed that he will run for
the vacancy left by Fischer as leader of the party, which brings
with it the title of deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
A coalition between the National Party of Australia, which
represents the interest of Australian farmers, and the Liberal
Party of Australia under the leadership of the prime minister won
last October's federal election to rule Australia for a second
three-year term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
