<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 07:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Religious Education May Return to Lebanese Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Education Minister
Mohammed Youssef Beydoun has announced a preliminary decision to
make religious education compulsory, a move critics warned could
exacerbate sectarian division, the Daily Star reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have finally decided to ... bring back religious education
to public schools after its years of absence," he said Tuesday
after a meeting with spokesmen of the country's 18 religious
parties.
</P>
<P>
The representatives of eight main denominations had unanimously
agreed to prepare separate school books on Islam and Christianity,
with a subsidiary chapter on the other religion, he said.
</P>
<P>
The decision, which has yet to get cabinet approval, would take
at least two years to come into effect, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Antoine Messara, member of the committee of academics which
worked on the school curriculum this year, criticized that
compulsory religious education "could be used as an excuse to
foster division and sectarian differences between students."
</P>
<P>
Religious teachings were taken off the state school curriculum
and made optional under former Prime Minister Rafik Hariri in a
bid to reduce sectarian tensions which were blamed for causing the
1975-1990 civil war.
</P>
<P>
But clerics criticized the move, and have repeatedly called
for its reintroduction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
