<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Parliament to Pass Referendum Bill First </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan Parliament resolved
Tuesday to pass the Referendum Bill before the Political
Organizations Bill after a four-hour stand-off.
</P>
<P>
The House, in an extraordinary sitting from morning till
evening, voted out the Legal Affairs Committee proposal that the
Parties Bill comes first, the New Vision newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Several MPs criticised Justice Minister Mayanja Nkangi, saying
that he introduced the bill too late, leaving members with on
choice but pass it to avoid a constitutional crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaker Francis Ayume had a hard task accommodating various
points of information, order, clarification and procedure in a
long-winding debate, unusually attended by over 30 ministers.
</P>
<P>
The Constitution demands that the Referendum bill be enacted
into law by mid-night on July 2. Campaigns for the referendum are
expected to follow up.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is expected to hold a referendum before July 3 of 2000
to decide the political system the country should adopt. The
multi-party MPs insist that general elections be held first and
that people are free to form other political parties.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's ruling National Resistance Movement denies that it is
a political party and allows no official activities of other
political organizations.
</P>
<P>
It is widely expected that the ruling party (the movement) will
get at least 80 percent votes in the coming referendum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
