<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hu Jintao Meets Leaders of Central Government Institutions in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao
this morning urged the central government institutions and
mainland-funded enterprises in Hong Kong to implement the "one
country, two systems" policy and abide by the Basic Law and the
laws of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
He also called on these institutions and firms to respect and
support the work of the SAR government under Chief Executive Tung
Chee Hwa.
</P>
<P>
Hu made the remarks during a meeting with leading members of
the central government institutions and mainland-funded
enterprises in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president said that the policies of "one country, two
systems," "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" and a high degree
of autonomy and the Basic Law have been fully implemented and Hong
Kong has maintained prosperity and stability since its return to
China two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Hu noted that the Hong Kong Branch of Xinhua News Agency, as an
authorized working organ of the central government, has maintained
close links with all the sectors in Hong Kong and has enhanced the
exchanges and cooperation between Hong Kong and the mainland areas.
</P>
<P>
He added that the branch has "effectively handled" some affairs
related to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Hu went on to say that the Office of the Commissioner of the
Chinese Foreign Ministry has handled foreign affairs related to
Hong Kong and helped the SAR government in external affairs, thus
promoting Hong Kong's liaison and cooperation with countries and
regions outside China and international organizations in the
economic, cultural and other spheres.
</P>
<P>
On the role of the Garrison of the People's Liberation Army in
Hong Kong, Hu said that the garrison has won the trust and acclaim
from local residents by performing its duties according to law and
safeguarding the country's sovereignty, unification, territorial
integrity and Hong Kong's security.
</P>
<P>
Hu pointed out that the work of these central government
institutions has enriched the theory and practice of "one country,
two systems" and contributed to Hong Kong's prosperity and
stability.
</P>
<P>
He said that the mainland-funded enterprises in Hong Kong, a
bridge and window of China in foreign economic relations, have
played an important role in promoting cooperation between Hong
Kong and the mainland areas and in providing funds and market
information for the economic developments in the mainland areas.
</P>
<P>
Hu recalled that soon after Hong Kong's return to China
President Jiang Zemin said that the great concept of "one country,
two systems" and the policies of "Hong Kong people governing Hong
Kong" and a high degree of autonomy advanced by Deng Xiaoping were
correct, that Hong Kong compatriots were capable of running Hong
Kong well, that the SAR government led by Tung Chee Hwa had the
wisdom and experience to cope with the complex situation and that
the great socialist motherland stood foursquare behind Hong Kong
in overcoming the difficulties and risks on its road of advance
and maintaining prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
Such observations, Hu added, constitute not only the basis for
the evaluation of Hong Kong's present situation and future
development, but an important guarantee for maintaining Hong Kong'
s long-term prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
Among those present at the meeting were SAR Chief Executive
Tung Chee Hwa; Jiang Enzhu, director of the Xinhua News Agency
Hong Kong Branch; Ma Yuzhen, commissioner of the Ministry of
Foreign Affairs in the SAR; and Xiong Ziren, commander of the
People's Liberation Army Garrison in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Liao Hui, director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of
the State Council, and Chen Fujin, deputy director of the General
Office of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China,
were also on hand.
</P>
<P>
Hu came to Hong Kong from Shenzhen Tuesday morning for the
unveiling of the Reunification Monument on the second anniversary
of Hong Kong's return to China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
