<HEADLINE> Indonesia Gears up For Brunei SEA Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A one million signatures campaign
and road race competition will mark Indonesia's efforts to garner
moral support from the public for its athletes competing at the
upcoming Southeast Asian (SEA) Games.
</P>
<P>
Nestle Milo, a chocolate beverage producer, and Indonesia's
educational department will encourage the students of primary
schools in Jakarta to post their messages and signatures on a
banner.
</P>
<P>
The campaign is expected to provide a morale booster for the
Indonesian athletes in their respective attempts to gain sporting
supremacy.
</P>
<P>
The organizers will also target people in the campaign
providing banners at a number of public facilities such as
shopping centers and sport centers throughout the country. One
million signatures -- should it be realized -- will make it into
the record book.
</P>
<P>
The banners will be displayed along the route of the 5-km and
10-km run competitions in a program entitled "Milo Indonesian
Champions' Run", in which a total of more than 7 million rupiah (1,
000 U.S. dollars will be offered in prizes.
</P>
<P>
The run, co-organized by the country's track and field
federation, will be held on August 1.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing is to give moral support to our
athletes. We are only contributing a small amount of money for
them. But they will receive support from all Indonesian people,
represented by one million of their signatures," marketing brand
manager of Nestle Indonesia Rudolf D. Hoeffelma said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
