<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Sports Council Insures SEA Games Athletes, Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's National Sports
Council (KONI) is providing two months of life insurance coverage
worth 5.83 billion rupiah (832,857 U.S. dollars) for 583 athletes
and officials from 20 sports taking part in the 20th Southeast
Asian (SEA) Games.
</P>
<P>
KONI official in charge of athletes development Mochamad
Hindarto said that athletes and officials were each entitled to 10
million rupiah in coverage for accidents during training here or
in competition at the biennial event in Brunei Darussalam from
August 7 to 15.
</P>
<P>
Provided by PT Pasaraya Life Insurance, the coverage began on
June 19 and lasts until August 19.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time we have insured our athletes for the
training period for the SEA Games. We want to anticipate any
unprecedented accidents during training and competition," Hindarto
was quoted by The Jakarta Post Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
He noted that KONI experienced difficulties in paying for the
medical costs of a rower injured at Jaliluhur dam during the 1997
Games here.
</P>
<P>
KONI planning and budget deputy Sudharno said the council
picked Pasaraya Life because it offered a more lucrative policy
premium.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta-based insurance company provided a monthly policy
premium of 7,000 rupiah for each participant.
</P>
<P>
"We only have to pay 8.162 million rupiah on the policy premium
for 583 participants. We have to pay in two stages," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Swimming Association (PRSI) technical division
official Lukman Niode welcomed KONI's initiative, saying athletes
would be freed from concerns over medical costs if they were
injured.
</P>
<P>
"The insurance coverage should be more effective in multi-event
competitions like the SEA Games. PRSI cannot provide the insurance
because it would cost us a lot of money. Moreover, not all
swimmers are consistent in their achievements," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
