<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smuggled Cultural Relics Returned to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Over 200 cultural relics
stolen from a 2,000-year-old tomb in Handan, north China's Hebei
Province, in 1997 and later smuggled to Britain and Canada were
recently returned to China.
</P>
<P>
The event marked the recovery of yet another batch of cultural
relics following the return of three bronze horses and a single
bronze piece from Britain in May 1998, according to Zhang Lizhu,
director of the Hebei Cultural Relics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
A nine-member gang broke into an imperial tomb in Handan,
capital of the ancient Zhao State, in 1997 and stole three bronze
horses, 209 pieces of other various treasures dating to the
Warring States Period (475-221 B.C.). Such relics are under top
state-level protection.
</P>
<P>
Gang members have since been arrested and are facing charges of
theft, trading and trafficking in cultural relics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
