<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Allocates Fund for Road Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
allocated 1 billion rupees (14.3 million U.S. dollars) under a
program for road development and maintenance in 1999, press
reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The program was launched in 1994 by Sri Lanka's Road
Development Authority (RDA) which is responsible for maintaining
and developing 11,285 kilometers of national highways and 4,200
bridges, the official Daily News reported.
</P>
<P>
The RDA spent 600 million rupees (9 million dollars) in 1998 on
building a total of 138 kilometers and the repair of 1,321 roads.
</P>
<P>
The RDA spent 1.2 billion rupees (20 million dollars) in 1997
to repair around 2,000 roads under the same program.
</P>
<P>
Consequently there was a marked improvement in the country's
road and highways network, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's original network of roads was laid under the
British period of rule which began in 1815. 
</P>
</TEXT>
