<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> We're the Underdog, German Women Insist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- When the men's national teams
of Germany and the United States met in last year's World Cup, the
Germans were heavy favorites. A defeat would have been considered
disgraceful.
</P>
<P>
With the women's teams from the same two countries set to meet
in a quarterfinal Thursday in suburban Jack Kent Cooke Stadium,
the public perception should be very different.
</P>
<P>
"People don't understand that the USA is the leading team,"
said Willi Henk, director of the German soccer federation's
technical program, which includes oversight of the women's
national team.
</P>
<P>
"They think the USA can't play soccer. They were more
interested in Germany against Brazil. "
</P>
<P>
The respective countries' head coaches paid one another
compliments Monday as they traveled to Washington to settle in for
a couple of days of training before the match.
</P>
<P>
"We have an edge in speed, but they are athletic," U.S. head
coach Tony DiCicco said. Midfielder Bettina Wiegmann is one of the
best players in the world, almost impossible to dispossess, a
class player in every sense of the word."
</P>
<P>
"They're a very proud team, a champion," DiCicco said of the
four-time European titlist. "They obviously weren't very happy
with their result against Brazil. In that country, it's politics,
soccer and religion, take your pick of what comes first."
</P>
<P>
German head coach Tina Theune-Meyer called the U.S. team the
cream of the tournament. "They are the best prepared in every way,
" she said. "You can see they are a team. They show it."
</P>
<P>
DiCicco said he has not decided whether to return to his
original starting 11 or give any of his super subs -- including
forward Shannon MacMillan, who had a goal and two assists against
DPR Korea-- another chance.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of times, it's about putting the hottest players on the
field, who's ready, who's confident," he said. "Those performances
yesterday, you have to take note."
</P>
<P>
The coach said he is aware of how difficult it is for players
like MacMillan and Tisha Venturini, the midfielder who scored
twice Sunday, to accept reserve roles after starting on the 1996
Olympic gold medal team. "I have as much respect for what they're
going through as I do for the starters, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Germany captain and midfield mainstay Martina Voss won't play
again in the World Cup after she aggravated a leg injury Sunday
against Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Voss, 31, who earned her 120th cap in that game, did not play
in the first two games to try to let the injury heal, but came out
25 minutes into the Brazil game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
