<HEADLINE> Mexico Makes Progress in World Cup with US-based Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's 10 American college
students had a difficult time adjusting to a national team, as
evidenced by an 0-3 finish in their first Women's World Cup soccer
appearance.
</P>
<P>
They also had to contend with the NCAA's hundreds of rules.
While the Mexican federation gave its players a whopping $20 per
day allowance, the students could take on $10 because of NCAA
regulations.
</P>
<P>
"I saved it up little by little to buy something little," said
Mexican goalkeeper Linnea Quinones (San Digego State) after her
team lost 2-0 to Italy on Sunday. "It sucks, but it's a rule."
</P>
<P>
Despite finishing the tournament undistinguished, the Mexicans
team left Foxboro Stadium with a measure of pride because of
subtle improvements over the course of there Group B matches. They
lost to Brazil 7-1, and Germany 6-0 before giving Italy a
challenge on an oppressive 90-degree day.
</P>
<P>
Exhausted but smiling, Mexico marched away talking about a big
future. "After the first two games, I was upset and frustrated,"
said Lisa Nanez, a former Santa Clara University player. "But I
was happy with the results today. I hope this team will prosper."
</P>
