<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Quake Forecast for Mexican Pacific Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The National Seismological
Service (NSS) Tuesday warned of a possible powerful earthquake in
Mexico's Pacific coastal area.
</P>
<P>
The National Center for the Prevention of Disasters also gave a
similar warning about the existence of "seismic breaches" in
Guerrero and Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
The organizations defined the seismic breach as a point of
shock between two plates deep in the earth, which accumulate
tension along the time until the friction surpasses the resistance
of the rocks and an earthquake occurs.
</P>
<P>
NSS director Javier Pacheco remembered that in the early years
of this century a great number of seisms were registered, that
broke the terrain in the region between Tapachula and Tonala, in
the southeast of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Pacheco said that the remoteness in time of those seisms makes
highly probable the eventuality of a powerful earthquake, that
could reach up to seven degrees on the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
He added that a similar circumstance is recorded in Guerrero,
where no teluric contingence has occurred again since 1911.
</P>
<P>
The expert also said that there are other areas with high
seismic risk, including the Tehuantepec "fracture" and the coasts
of Colima and Michoacan, in the Mexican Pacific coast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
