<HEADLINE> Nepali Cabinet Expanded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Krishna
Prasad Bhattarai expanded his cabinet Wednesday by inducting 17
new faces including one woman and five from the far-western region
of the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The 32-member new cabinet includes 19 ministers, eight state
ministers and five assistant ministers.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen ministers of the old cabinet remain. Taranath Ranabhat
resigned as minister for law and justice and parliamentary affairs
before he took office as speaker of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Bhattarai holds concurrently the portfolios of
defense and royal palace affairs.
</P>
<P>
Ram Sharan Mahat was assigned foreign minister while Purna
Bahadur Khadka took over the powerful home ministry plus the
ministry of information and communications.
</P>
<P>
Kamala Pand is the only female in the cabinet. She is minister
of state for women and social welfare.
</P>
<P>
Five lawmakers from the far-western region were included into
the cabinet this time. Lawmakers elected from the region had
expressed their unhappiness over Bhattarai's failure to include
any one of them in the 16-member cabinet formed on May 31.
</P>
<P>
The region returned the Nepali Congress candidates in all its
18 constituencies in the general elections held in May. The Nepali
Congress won 111 of the 205 seats in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Bhattarai said that he would complete the cabinet formation in
three phases.
</P>
<P>
It is the first majority government in Nepal in four and half
years.
</P>
<P>
Six governments had ruled the kingdom in the past four and half
years after the mid-term polls in November 1994 produced a hung
parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
