<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Prime Minister Viktor
Klima said here Tuesday that his country is concerned about the
death penalty that Turkey has meted out to Kurdish rebel leader
Abdullah Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
Austria is in principle against the death penalty, Klima said.
He hoped that the transparency should be kept when other possible
lawful measures are taken, such as opening up an international
court and trying Ocalan again.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Wolfgang
Schuessel pointed out that every country has appropriate rights
against terrorism, but to execute Ocalan will intensify the hatred
between the two sides and obstruct permanent political resolutions
to the Kurdish issue.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan, leader of the Kurdish Workers' Party, was sentenced to
death Tuesday morning by a security court in Turkey. The verdict
is yet to be confirmed by an appeal court, the Turkish Parliament
and Turkish President Suleyman Demirel. 
</P>
