<HEADLINE> New Investments Hit First Half Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Board of Investment has
met its target of 100 billion pesos (2.5 billion U.S. dollars) in
fresh equity investment of the year, Business World reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Melito Salazar, managing chief of the government body, told
reporters Tuesday that they surpassed the target after the agency
approved three big-ticket projects just this month,
</P>
<P>
However, the approved fresh investments totaling 100.27 billion
pesos only represent a 34 percent drop from the year-ago 152.3
billion pesos (3.8 billion dollars) .
</P>
<P>
Total investments this month alone reached 68.49 billion pesos
(1.7 billion dollars), up 270 percent from the 1998 level of 18.4
billion pesos (460 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The achievement is reached largely due to a 44.46-billion-peso
(1.1-billion-dollar) refinery conversion project of Petron
Petropower Corp.
</P>
<P>
Petron's project will be implemented under a joint-venture
arrangement with U.S.-based Foster Wheeler Power Systems.
</P>
<P>
Other two major projects are the development of integrated
medical centers with an injection of 6 billions pesos (1.5 billion
dollars) and a new public utility articulated bus system with 3.8
billion pesos (950 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
For the second semester, the investment agency is targeting 300
billion pesos (7.5 billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
