<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Asked to Grant Foreign Troop Passage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The National Coordination Center for
Logistic Support between Bulgaria and NATO has so far received
requests from Poland, Turkey, the Czech Republic and Hungary for
the passage of troops through the Bulgarian territory, Colonel
Vassil Vurbanov, head of the center, told a news conference
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The first Polish echelon which entered the country on Monday
has already left Bulgaria and another one is expected to enter on
Tuesday, Vurbanov said. A total of seven Polish echelons are
scheduled to pass through Bulgaria, he added.
</P>
<P>
Early July will see the transit of the next batch of troops:
the first of three Czech trainloads on July 1 (129 soldiers and 66
military vehicles) and the first of six Turkish trainloads and a
road column on July 3 (372 troops and 60 vehicles), Vurbanov said.
</P>
<P>
The Czech train will enter Bulgaria from Romania via Rousse (on
the Danube) and will leave the country via the Koulata checkpoint
on the Greek border. The Turks will come via the Kapitan Andreevo
checkpoint and will leave Bulgaria via Gueshevo (on the Macedonian
border), Vurbanov noted.
</P>
<P>
Russia has not requested permission for passage of ground
echelons via Bulgaria, Vurbanov said, adding that no request to
use the Black Sea port of Bourgas for transit of troops has been
made either. "Nonetheless, we are prepared in case we receive a
request."
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant-General Tencho Dobrev, deputy chief of general staff
of the Bulgarian Army, said that border formalities for the troops
will include only documentation clearance as they are entitled to
preferential customs treatment.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's agreement with NATO on the transit passage of allied
troops and equipment via the country under the Joint Guardian
operation was ratified by Parliament on June 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
