<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Military Chief Warns of Mass Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Defense Forces (TNI)
Chief Gen. Wiranto Tuesday warned of possible mass rallies ahead
of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) general session which
may create conflict between the people and the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
"Such rallies will result in conflict on the streets between
the people, Polri (National Police) and the TNI," Wiranto said.
</P>
<P>
The MPR, the country's highest decision-making body, will meet
in November to elect the country's next president.
</P>
<P>
The 700-strong MPR is made up of 200 government appointees and
500 members of the House of Representatives (DPR). The June 7
election will choose 462 legislators. A further 38 seats are
reserved for the powerful military.
</P>
<P>
As no single party will attain an absolute majority in these
elections, the road to the presidency is expected to be bumpy this
year.
</P>
<P>
Megawati Soekarnoputri, whose Indonesian Democratic Party of
Struggle (PDI-P) held a convincing lead in the provisional tally,
is the front-runner for the presidency. She is in competition with
President B.J. Habibie who has been nominated for the presidency
by the ruling Golkar Party, which trailed PDI-P in the tally.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto, who is also defense and security minister, said mass
rallies in support of presidential candidates are a "wrong step"
and will mislead the people.
</P>
<P>
"Now it is time to maintain and develop the existing good
situation here. The elections were held safely. That is a positive
sign for us ahead of the MPR general session," national
newspapers Wednesday quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto called on the public, experts and politicians in
particular, to comment on the political situation only with
"realistic and soothing" statements.
</P>
<P>
He said common people do not ask too much but only wish for
peace, adequate food and clothing, health security and schools for
their children.
</P>
<P>
"I think the voice of the grassroots must be heard. By
listening to their voice, politicians who will determine the
future of the nation through a democratic process may find the
best solution which is certainly not in rhetoric that will only
confuse the people," he added.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with University of Indonesia lecturers on Tuesday,
Wiranto said that the TNI will remain neutral in the middle of the
battle between the camps of Megawati and Habibie.
</P>
<P>
The TNI would not side with either Habibie's or Megawati's
camp, but with the people, Wiranto stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
