<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rio Summit to Act As Pole Against U.S.: Brazilian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso said here Tuesday that the first Latin
America (LA), European Union (EU) and Caribbean Summit will act as
a pole against the United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held at the end of the summit,
Cardoso said the two-day meeting gave more stress to the world-
wide economic scene, with regard to the countries that are in
greater need, such as those in Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the press conference were Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder and European
Commission President Jacques Santer.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso said that the strengthening of the euro, the currency
used by 11 of the 15 EU countries, will be a good alternative to
other currencies in the future.
</P>
<P>
He also said that it was possible that there would be a Latin
American currency in the future.
</P>
<P>
By focusing on the expansion of dialogue, Cardoso said, the
summit was in favor of economic diversification and would have
repercussions for the 21st century in the face of economic
globalization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
