<HEADLINE> Philippines' Telecom Giant Buys Home Cable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Telecom giant Philippine Long
Distance Telephone Co. (PLDT) announced Tuesday the acquisition of
Philippine Home Cable holdings Inc. and Internet service provider
Infocom Technologies Inc, for a total of 3.11 billion pesos (77.75
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Manila Times quoted Wednesday PLDT Senior Vice President
Antonio Samson as saying that the purchases form part of PLDT's
effort to diversify into voice and data services.
</P>
<P>
PLDT is the Philippines' largest telephone company which
dominates more than 80 percent of the country's telephone market.
</P>
<P>
The paper said PLDT and one of its subsidiary will acquire Home
Cable from the Soriano family for 3.03 billion pesos (75.75
million U.S. dollars) on July 8.
</P>
<P>
Home Cable is one of the country's largest cable operators and
has a subscriber base of 120,000.
</P>
<P>
PLDT said it will also purchase an additional 30.8 percent
stake in Infocom for 80.2 million pesos (2 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
PLDT currently has a 69.2 percent stake in Infocom and the
later will become a wholly-owned subsidiary of the telecom giant
once the acquisition is completed next month, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Infocom, one of the leading providers of internet and data
communications services, currently has a total subscriber base of
70,000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the paper said PLDT hopes to begin its local metered
telephone service by the first quarter of next year following the
completion of an ongoing review of the planned service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
