<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Del Piero to Stay at Juventus Soccer Club Till 2004 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Italy star Alessandro Del Piero on
Tuesday extended his contract with Turin side Juventus soccer club
until 2004.
</P>
<P>
The five-year contract, agreed after months of hard bargaining,
is believed to make the 25-year-old the highest-paid player in the
world.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency ANSA, Del Piero would get nine
billion lire (5 million U.S. dollars) for next year, the last of
his current contract, rising to 10.5 billion lire (5.9 million U.S.
dollars) in 2004.
</P>
<P>
With marketing rights thrown in, the package outstrips
Christian Vieri's payload inked into his recent record-breaking 49
million U.S. dollars move from Lazio to Inter Milan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Italy northwestern city of
Turin, Del Piero made light of the suggestion that he was the
world's wealthiest soccer star.
</P>
<P>
"There are certain things money can't give you... my aspiration
was to start winning again quickly with Juventus, not become the
richest player in the world."
</P>
<P>
Del Piero is still recovering from a November ligament
operation but said he hopes to be back in light training in July.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to observers and fans not to be too hard on him in
his initial outings next season, when he will still be feeling his
way back to match fitness.
</P>
<P>
Del Piero was widely expected to be one of the stars of last
year's World Cup in France but his performances disappointed,
after a great year with Juve that saw them take the Italian
championship but fail in the European Cup.
</P>
<P>
His serious knee injury came after a late-summer of polemics in
which he crossed swords with former Roma coach Zdenek Zeman, who
suggested he and other Juve players may have used performance-
enhancing substances.
</P>
<P>
Del Piero is currently suing Zeman over the claims.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Juventus's owner, Italian car-giant FIAT's Former
boss Gianni Agnelli came up with one of his customary dry remarks:
"They are all happy about the renewal of Del Piero's contract, but
I think he is the happiest."  
</P>
</TEXT>
