<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces Medicare Reform Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton,
announcing his Medicare reform program here Tuesday, proposed a
new universal prescription drug benefit for Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
"This is a drug benefit our seniors can afford at a price
America can afford," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The new drug benefit, if approved by Congress, would be
available as an option for those 65 and older and for the disabled
beginning in 2002. It would cost the government 118 billion
dollars over 10 years, administration officials estimate.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's universal drug benefit will cover half the cost of
drugs, up to 2000 dollars a year, for a monthly premium of 24
dollars. During the first six years of the program, which begins
in 2002, the coverage will rise to 5000 dollars a year and the
monthly premium to 44 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said his Medicare rescue plan will be paid for with
794 dollars over the next 15 years, all of it coming from
expected federal budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
The White House said that the drug proposal in only a small
part of its plan to modernize the 34-year-old Medicare program,
enacted to provide health insurance for the elderly. The program
currently covers 39 million elderly and disabled Americans.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's Medicare reform program reflects a major change in
the elderly population in the United States which is not only
larger and growing but living longer and healthier than in the
past.
</P>
<P>
In 1970, about 20 million people were covered by the
entitlement program. Today that number has nearly doubled and is
growing swiftly as the Baby Boom generation begins to retire. By
2011 it will more that double again with more than 77 million
people eligible for benefits. In 2048, 81 million people are
expected to participate in the program.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's announcement sets up what is expected to be a bitter
fight with Congress dominated by the Republican Party. Many
Republicans say that much money is not needed to save Medicare,
especially for new benefits, and the extra surplus funds should
instead be used for a deeper tax cut.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Dennis Hastert and Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, both Republican, issued a joint statement Tuesday praising
Clinton's efforts to provide better drug coverage for retirees
but questioned the need to give government subsidies for the
Medicare beneficiaries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
