<HEADLINE> U.N. to Convene Meeting on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A special meeting will be
held on Wednesday morning, during which the United Nations is
expected to ask the participating foreign ministers and other
high-level officials for staff and money to finance the U.N.
mission in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, a senior U.N. official
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, chaired by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Anna,
will begin at the U.N. headquarters at 8:00 a.m. EST, he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to ask for money as well as personnel from
those attending the one-day meeting that includes 10 foreign
ministers among 16 nations, who are described as "friends of the
Secretary-General for Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
Shen Guofang, China's deputy permanent representative to the
United Nations, will take part in the coming meeting as the senior
representative of Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, a
spokesman for the Chinese Missions, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The most pressing need is for an international police force to
tackle crime that has flourished with the exit of Serbian police
and military forces and the return of more than 300,000 ethnic
Albanian refugees. Only a small U.N. contingent has arrived from
the international mission in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
So far some 18 countries have said they would send 900
police, which should begin pouring into Kosovo every five days
next month at 150-200 in each contingent, Eckhard said. They
come from Austria, Bangladesh, Bulgaria, Canada, Denmark,
Egypt, Italy, Kenya, Lithuania, Malaysia, Nepal, Pakistan,
Romania, Tanzania, Turkey, Britain, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting will be the foreign ministers of Belgium,
Finland, France, Germany, Greece, Italy, the Netherlands, Spain,
Turkey and Britain and the United States. Other nations
represented, in addition to Ambassador Shen, will be Canada,
Denmark, Japan and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from the European Union, which is in charge of
reconstruction in Kosovo, and the Organisation for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, responsible for institution building, as
well as the Organisation of the Islamic Conference have also been
invited to the four-hour meeting.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to announce who will be his special
representative or chief administrator for the entire operation,
now run temporarily by Sergio de Mello, the Brazilian U.N.
undersecretary-general for humanitarian affairs. He has said he
would choose a European, the senior official said.
</P>
<P>
But a one more portfolio is added to the existing list: a
deputy special representative for the U.N. mission in Kosovo,
known as UNMIK. "The deputy is to coordinate the four pillars of
the U.N. mission," he said.
</P>
<P>
Both Britain and France are vying for the post and some
U.N. officials prefer Martti Ahtisaari, who however does not
finish his term as president of Finland for another six
months.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. mission will carry out its mandate without undermining
the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia, as stipulated by the June 10 Security Council
resolution, the senior official added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
