<HEADLINE> Death Sentence to Ocalan Distances Turkey From Europe, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The death sentence handed to Kurdish
rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan by a Turkish court Wednesday risks
widening the divide between Europe and Turkey, Italian Prime
Minister Massimo D'Alema said.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency ANSA, D'Alema, speaking on the
sidelines of the European Union-Latin American summit in Rio de
Janeiro of Brazil, said that both the sentence itself and Turkey's
handling of the trial were "very grave."
</P>
<P>
He said that "all this risks distancing Turkey from Europe".
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Italian Lower House's foreign affairs committee
in an approved motion urged the government to undertake "forceful"
moves with Turkey to obtain the commutation of the death sentence
handed down against Ocalan
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Italian courts are still considering whether Ocalan
can be granted political asylum, on the basis of a suit filed by
his lawyers before he left Italy.
</P>
<P>
Italy refused to hand Ocalan to Turkey when he arrived in Rome
on November 12 last year because its constitution forbids
extraditing suspects to countries where the death penalty is still
used.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan left Italy on January 16 for an unknown destination
after authorities persuaded him to leave voluntarily. He left
before his request for political asylum was answered by Italian
aUhorities.
</P>
<P>
The 50-year-old leader of the Kurdistan Workers' Party turned
up again in Kenya four months ago when he was seized by Turkish
special agents and taken to the high-security prison where his
trial concluded Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
