<DOCNO> XIE19990630.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italians More Afraid of Thieves Than Mafia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Italians are more afraid of common
thieves than they are of organized crime, according to a report by
the Italian Social Investment Studies Center (Censis) presented
Wednesday at the national conference on Security and Legality
which is held in Sicilian city of Catania.
</P>
<P>
Although they are less spectacular than mafia-style crime, the
report found, purse snatching and house break-ins have contributed
more to increasing insecurity among Italians who are more and more
asking for law enforcement and administrative officials to do
something to make their communities safer.
</P>
<P>
Crimes like car theft or break-ins, the study added, have a
more direct impact on citizens and aggravates unease even among
those who have not been victims of these crimes.
</P>
<P>
Looking at organized crime, the Censis report found that the
mafia had gone through a radical change and now preferred a more
low-key, although no less dangerous, presence.
</P>
<P>
In other words, the era of the flashy bombs and gangland
slayings has given way to the low profile and almost invisible
presence which creates the illusion that tensions have subsided
and normality returned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
